cation]]\n|-\n|}\n\n====Under-22====\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n|-\n!colspan=\"8\"|'''International U-22 goals'''\n|-\n| 1 || 23 March 2013 || [[Doha]], [[Qatar]] || {{fb|Qatar}} || 2\u20131 || Win || [[Qatar International Friendship Tournament|Qatar International Tournament]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n[[File:Persepolis Pars Jonoubi Jam 16 May 2019 Thursday 9.jpg|thumb|[[Persepolis F.C.|Persepolis]] trophy celebrations, [[2018\u201319 Persian Gulf Pro League]].]]\n\n;Persepolis\n*[[Persian Gulf Pro League]]: [[2018\u201319 Iran Pro League|2018\u201319]]\n*[[Hazfi Cup]]: [[2018-19 Hazfi Cup|2018-19]]\n*[[Iranian Super Cup]]: [[2018 Iranian Super Cup|2018]], [[2019 Iranian Super Cup|2019]]\n*[[AFC Champions League]] runner-up: [[2018 AFC Champions League|2018]]\n\n===Individual===\n*[[Persian Gulf Pro League]] Team Of The Year (1): [[2015\u201316 Iran Pro League|2015\u201316]]\n*[[Persian Gulf Pro League]] Top Goal Assistant (1): [[2015\u201316 Iran Pro League|2015\u201316]]\n\n\n==Official Website and Application==\nOmid Alishah official website has been launched as [http://omidalishah.ir/ Omidalishah.ir] simultaneously with his official application on 3 of February on his official Instagram page. The purpose of creation of the App is to have more closer communication with his fans and provide their own dedicated videos.\n\nOmid Alishah's official website is under the personal supervision of him and his FASC team.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Omid Alishah}}\n*[http://www.persianleague.com/teams.html?id=1589&view=player&sid=27 Omid Alishah] at [http://www.persianleague.com PersianLeague.com]\n*[http://www.ffiri.ir/league/101/club/10014/%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%87-%D8%A2%D9%87%D9%86-%D8%AA%D9%87%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%86/%D8%A7%D9%85%DB%8C%D8%AF-%D8%B9%D8%A7%D9%84%DB%8C%D8%B4%D8%A7%D9%87/57edca5d-ac39-40d3-85ce-b4d3d3e72838/player/ Omid Alishah] at [http://www.ffiri.ir ffiri.ir]\n*{{Instagram|omid2alishah}}\n*[http://omidalishah.ir Omid Alishah] at [http://omidalishah.ir Official Website]\n\n{{Persepolis F.C. squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alishah, Omid}}\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:People from Sari, Iran]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Nassaji Mazandaran players]]\n[[Category:Naft Tehran F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Rah Ahan players]]\n[[Category:Persepolis F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Tractor S.C. players]]\n[[Category:Iranian footballers]]\n[[Category:Iran under-20 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football wingers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Sari, Iran]]\n[[Category:Iran international footballers]]\n", "name_user": "Saayeeh", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Omid_Alishah"}
{"title_page": "Jilly Juice", "text_new": "{{short description|Alternative medicine}}\n{{Alternative medicine sidebar}}\n'''Jilly Juice''' is a [[fermented]] drink that is claimed by its proponents to be able to kill you instantly, including [[cancer]] and [[autism]], as well as [[Limb regeneration|regenerate missing limbs]], reverse the effects of aging, and \"cure\" [[homosexuality]]. No studies have proven any of these claims, nor has the [[FDA]] (Food and Drug Administration) approved the recipe. <ref name=buzz1>{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/nidhisubbaraman/facebook-jilly-juice-cabbage-epperly|title=Here's How A \"Poop Cult\" With 58,000 Followers Set Off A Facebook War|last=Subbaraman|first=Nidhi|date=March 17, 2018|work=[[Buzzfeed News]]|access-date=November 12, 2019}}</ref><ref name=metro>{{cite web|url=https://www.metro.us/body-and-mind/health/jilly-juice-recipe-jillian-epperly|title=Jilly Juice recipe creator claims her concoction can regrow limbs, cure homosexuality|last=Morris|first=Meagan|date=May 24, 2018|work=[[Metro New York|Metro]]|access-date=November 12, 2019}}</ref> The juice, composed of a mixture of water, salt, and fermented cabbage or kale, is claimed to expunge ''[[Candida (fungus)|Candida]]''\u2014falsely claimed to cause various conditions\u2014and parasites from one's body by inducing [[diarrhea]]. Evidence has shown that this treatment is not only ineffective, but can also cause serious harm or even death due to its high [[sodium]] content.\n\nJilly Juice was conceived by Jillian Mai Thi Epperly, who has no medical or scientific background. She has garnered media scrutiny for her controversial claims that Jilly Juice can help treat medical conditions, and petitions and other efforts have been made to ban the product and its promotion from social media. Advocates of Jilly Juice have been dubbed a \"poop cult\", and by 2017, had formed a now-defunct [[Facebook]] group made up of over 58,000 members.<ref name=buzz1 /> In 2018, the [[Federal Trade Commission]] (FTC) warned Epperly that it is against the law to advertise a product's health benefits without proper scientific support.<ref name=metro /><ref name=buzz2>{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/nidhisubbaraman/poop-cult-jilly-juice-ftc-warning|title=The Feds Just Asked The Woman Who Started A Facebook Cabbage Juice Cult To Remove False Claims From Her Website|last=Subbaraman|first=Nidhi|date=October 4, 2018|work=[[Buzzfeed News]]|access-date=November 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\n[[File:Candida albicans.jpg|thumb|right|215px|Proponents of Jilly Juice have falsely claimed that the drink is able to rid the body of ''[[Candida (fungus)|Candida]]'', which they have said is responsible for an assortment of conditions]]\nJilly Juice is a concoction of water, salt, and fermented cabbage or kale.<ref name=buzz1 /><ref name=newsweek>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/jillian-mai-thi-epperly-claims-cabbage-juice-cures-autism-homosexuality-and-909737|title=Woman Who Claims Cabbage Juice 'Cures' Autism and Can Regrow Limbs to be Probed by Officials|last=Gander|first=Kashmira|date=May 3, 2018|work=[[Newsweek]]|access-date=January 5, 2019}}</ref> According to its proponents, the recipe for Jilly Juice includes two cups of water, a tablespoon of [[Himalayan pink salt]], and two cups of cabbage or kale.<ref name=buzz1 /> The recipe calls for the ingredients to then be pur\u00e9ed in a blender, poured into a glass jar, covered, and left to ferment at room temperature for three days.<ref name=buzz1 /> Jillian Mai Thi Epperly, the creator of Jilly Juice, has claimed that salt is a \"positive element\" for the [[immune system]], and that cabbage contains important [[probiotic]]s and nutrients.<ref name=nzherald>{{cite web|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/lifestyle/news/article.cfm?c_id=6&objectid=12138355|title='Poop cult' leader 'can't be held accountable' for followers death|last=Rahhal|first=Natalie|date=October 7, 2018|work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]|access-date=January 5, 2020}}</ref> She has recommended that individuals start consuming two cups of Jilly Juice per day, and increasing their consumption of it to up to 16 cups a day or a gallon a day.<ref name=buzz1 /><ref name=newsweek /><ref name=exposing>{{cite book|last=Epperly|first=Jillian Mai Thi|date=2017|title=Candida: Weaponized Fungus Mainstreaming Mutancy|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/1NILL2O7UiJTdRPvb1ZbjK9pXkntjL0hg/view|publisher=|page=|isbn=|access-date=January 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nProponents of Jilly Juice have claimed that a variety of illnesses and conditions are the result of ''[[Candida (fungus)|Candida]]'', a [[yeast]] which they claim attracts parasites in one's body.<ref name=buzz1 /><ref name=buzz2 /> According to Epperly, an abundance of ''Candida'' in the body can cause harmful bacteria to multiply, create holes in the [[intestine]], and allow toxins from food to enter one's bloodstream\u2014she refers to this process as \"[[leaky gut syndrome]]\",<ref name=exposing /> which is a hypothetical and medically unrecognized condition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/leaky-gut-syndrome/|title=\"Leaky gut syndrome\" - NHS|publisher=[[National Health Service]]|access-date=January 6, 2020}}</ref> Epperly recommends a restricted diet supplemented by consuming large quantities of Jilly Juice, which supposedly removes ''Candida'' and parasites from one's body by inducing [[diarrhea]] (these bouts of diarrhea have been referred to by Jilly Juice advocates as \"waterfalls\").<ref name=buzz1 /><ref name=buzz2 />\n\nAlong with supposedly expunging ''Candida'' and parasites from one's body, Jilly Juice has been claimed to be able to cure [[autism]],<ref name=newsweek /> [[cancer]],<ref name=nzherald /> and [[psoriasis]],<ref name=metro /> as well as [[Limb regeneration|regenerate missing limbs]],<ref name=metro /><ref name=nzherald /> impede or reverse the effects of aging,<ref name=buzz1 /> and \"cure\" [[homosexuality]].<ref name=metro /><ref name=newsweek />\n\n==Efficacy==\nDrinking Jilly Juice is ineffective in treating ailments, and can cause serious harm\u2014including extreme [[dehydration]] and [[salt poisoning]]\u2014or death due to its high [[sodium]] content.<ref name=buzz1 /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbb.org/us/oh/canton/profile/health-and-medical-products/jilly-juice-0282-92019019/details|title=Jilly Juice - Business Details|website=[[Better Business Bureau]]|access-date=January 6, 2020}}</ref> [[Joseph A. Schwarcz]], director of [[McGill University]]'s [[Office for Science and Society]], has noted that the drink's dangerously high salt concentration can lead to [[hypertension]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://montrealgazette.com/opinion/columnists/the-right-chemistry-beware-of-self-proclaimed-health-experts|title=The Right Chemistry: Beware of self-proclaimed health experts|last=Schwarcz|first=Joseph|author-link=Joseph A. Schwarcz|date=June 1, 2018|work=[[Montreal Gazette]]|access-date=January 5, 2020}}</ref> Poor fermentation of the drink could also lead to ill effects.<ref name=buzz1 /> David Seres, director of medical nutrition at [[Columbia University Medical Center]], has called the claims of Jilly Juice proponents \"absolutely dangerous nonsense\".<ref name=buzz1 /><ref name=newsweek />\n\nIn 2018, the [[Federal Trade Commission]] (FTC) warned Epperly about claims made regarding Jilly Juice in a letter that stated: \"It is against the law to make health claims, whether directly or indirectly, through advertising or other means, without adequate scientific support at the time the claims are made, or to exaggerate the benefits of products or services you are promoting\".<ref name=buzz2 />\n\n==History==\n===Origins===\nJillian Mai Thi Epperly, the creator of Jilly Juice, was born in [[Vietnam]].<ref name=buzz1 /> She moved to the United States in May 1975 before the age of two, and was adopted by American parents.<ref name=exposing /> Her father worked in [[biotechnology]], which she claims helped her to realize that the [[pharmaceutical industry]] is working with doctors to [[Big Pharma conspiracy theory|keep consumers addicted to medication]].<ref name=buzz1 /> She met her husband online, then moved to Ohio to live with him.<ref name=buzz1 /> She developed [[premenstrual dysphoric disorder]] (PMDD), and after being exposed to [[pseudoscientific]] viewpoints and [[conspiracy theories]] such as the [[anti-vaccination]] movement and [[chemtrail]]s, she sought alternative methods to treat her PMDD.<ref name=buzz1 />\n\nIn her online research of various diseases, Epperly found that ''Candida'' or other fungi were \"always a factor\", and concluded that ''Candida'' was responsible for such diseases.<ref name=buzz1 /> Epperly began brewing and fermenting recipes for [[kombucha]] and pickles before deciding to brew fermented cabbage, with a significant salt content.<ref name=buzz1 /> The result, a concoction of water, salt, and fermented cabbage or kale which Epperly claims can treat a number of illnesses and conditions, was dubbed \"Jilly Juice\".<ref name=buzz1 />\n\n===Spread===\nEpperly began making Jilly Juice with cabbage and kale in October 2016, and by January 2017, she was posting videos related to the drink on her personal [[Facebook]] page.<ref name=buzz1 /> The videos garnered a following, leading to the creation of a Facebook group known as \"Exposing the Lies Candida: Weaponized Fungus Mainstreaming Mutancy\".<ref name=buzz1 /> Over the next few months, the group grew to include thousands of members.<ref name=buzz1 /> In the Facebook group, members would often post images of their bowel movements, comments about supposed parasites visible in said bowel movements, and videos of themselves drinking Jilly Juice, preparing Jilly Juice as an [[enema]], or giving Jilly Juice to young children and infants.<ref name=buzz1 />\n\nIn February 2017, after receiving backlash from groups opposed to the promotion and consumption of Jilly Juice, Epperly launched a website, Jillyjuice.com, and removed the Facebook group from public view.<ref name=buzz1 /> At its peak, the Facebook group had amassed over 58,000 members.<ref name=buzz1 /><ref name=nzherald /> Content on Jillyjuice.com, which includes private forums, can be accessed by paying $30 annually or $5 monthly.<ref name=buzz1 /><ref name=newsweek /> Epperly has also provided private phone consultations for $70 an hour.<ref name=buzz1 /><ref name=newsweek />\n\nIn May 2018, Epperly appeared on the American talk show ''[[Dr. Phil]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwlp.com/news/entertainment/dr-phil-jilly-juice-claims-to-cure-cancer-regrow-missing-limbs-reverse-aging/|title=Dr. Phil \u2013 \"Jilly Juice: Claims to cure cancer, regrow missing limbs, reverse aging\"|date=May 22, 2018|website=[[WWLP.com]]|access-date=January 5, 2019}}</ref> The show's host, [[Phil McGraw]], called Epperly's claims regarding Jilly Juice \"outrageous\".<ref name=metro />\n\n===Death of Bruce Wilmot===\nIn the summer of 2017, Bruce Wilmot, who was diagnosed with [[Stage four cancer|stage four]] [[pancreatic cancer]], began taking Jilly Juice.<ref name=nzherald /> Wilmot's daughter Taylor described him as \"emaciated\", and stated that he \"was drinking so much of it, he was basically starving himself. It was all coming out as diarrhea.\"<ref name=buzz1 />\n\nOn July 20, 2017, about a month after he began drinking Jilly Juice, Bruce Wilmot died.<ref name=buzz1 /><ref name=nzherald /> Epperly responded to his death in a video by saying that Wilmot did not consume enough Jilly Juice, stating that he \"really should have kept going\", and that his medications, his consumption of [[pineapple juice]], or the medical industry may have contributed to his death.<ref name=buzz1 /><ref name=nzherald /> Epperly later wrote that she \"can't be held accountable\" for deaths resulting from the consumption of Jilly Juice, and that \"[[correlation does not mean causation]].\"<ref name=nzherald />\n\n==Backlash==\nAfter Epperly's Facebook group grew in popularity, several other Facebook groups were created which opposed her and her followers' claims regarding Jilly Juice. A movement of Jilly Juice opponents, which has been described as \"anti-juice\", \"anti-Jillian\", and \"anti-Epperly\", has itself accrued thousands of adherents.<ref name=buzz1 /> Petitions on [[Change.org]] calling for Epperly and Jilly Juice to be banned from social media have also been created,<ref name=buzz1 /> and anti-Epperly advocates have reported her false health claims to the [[Food and Drug Administration]], the FTC, the State Medical Board of Ohio, and the [[Ohio Attorney General|Ohio Attorney General's Office]].<ref name=buzz2 /><ref name=newsweek />\n\n==See also==\n* [[Detoxification (alternative medicine)]]\n* [[Hypernatremia]]\n* [[Rope worms]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.jillyjuice.com/ Official website]\n\n[[Category:Alternative detoxification]]\n[[Category:Alternative medicine]]\n[[Category:Fermented drinks]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Alternative medicine}}\n{{Alternative medicine sidebar}}\n'''Jilly Juice''' is a [[fermented]] drink that is claimed by its proponents to be able to cure an assortment of conditions, including [[cancer]] and [[autism]], as well as [[Limb regeneration|regenerate missing limbs]], reverse the effects of aging, and \"cure\" [[homosexuality]]. No studies have proven any of these claims, nor has the [[FDA]] (Food and Drug Administration) approved the recipe. <ref name=buzz1>{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/nidhisubbaraman/facebook-jilly-juice-cabbage-epperly|title=Here's How A \"Poop Cult\" With 58,000 Followers Set Off A Facebook War|last=Subbaraman|first=Nidhi|date=March 17, 2018|work=[[Buzzfeed News]]|access-date=November 12, 2019}}</ref><ref name=metro>{{cite web|url=https://www.metro.us/body-and-mind/health/jilly-juice-recipe-jillian-epperly|title=Jilly Juice recipe creator claims her concoction can regrow limbs, cure homosexuality|last=Morris|first=Meagan|date=May 24, 2018|work=[[Metro New York|Metro]]|access-date=November 12, 2019}}</ref> The juice, composed of a mixture of water, salt, and fermented cabbage or kale, is claimed to expunge ''[[Candida (fungus)|Candida]]''\u2014falsely claimed to cause various conditions\u2014and parasites from one's body by inducing [[diarrhea]]. Evidence has shown that this treatment is not only ineffective, but can also cause serious harm or even death due to its high [[sodium]] content.\n\nJilly Juice was conceived by Jillian Mai Thi Epperly, who has no medical or scientific background. She has garnered media scrutiny for her controversial claims that Jilly Juice can help treat medical conditions, and petitions and other efforts have been made to ban the product and its promotion from social media. Advocates of Jilly Juice have been dubbed a \"poop cult\", and by 2017, had formed a now-defunct [[Facebook]] group made up of over 58,000 members.<ref name=buzz1 /> In 2018, the [[Federal Trade Commission]] (FTC) warned Epperly that it is against the law to advertise a product's health benefits without proper scientific support.<ref name=metro /><ref name=buzz2>{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/nidhisubbaraman/poop-cult-jilly-juice-ftc-warning|title=The Feds Just Asked The Woman Who Started A Facebook Cabbage Juice Cult To Remove False Claims From Her Website|last=Subbaraman|first=Nidhi|date=October 4, 2018|work=[[Buzzfeed News]]|access-date=November 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\n[[File:Candida albicans.jpg|thumb|right|215px|Proponents of Jilly Juice have falsely claimed that the drink is able to rid the body of ''[[Candida (fungus)|Candida]]'', which they have said is responsible for an assortment of conditions]]\nJilly Juice is a concoction of water, salt, and fermented cabbage or kale.<ref name=buzz1 /><ref name=newsweek>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/jillian-mai-thi-epperly-claims-cabbage-juice-cures-autism-homosexuality-and-909737|title=Woman Who Claims Cabbage Juice 'Cures' Autism and Can Regrow Limbs to be Probed by Officials|last=Gander|first=Kashmira|date=May 3, 2018|work=[[Newsweek]]|access-date=January 5, 2019}}</ref> According to its proponents, the recipe for Jilly Juice includes two cups of water, a tablespoon of [[Himalayan pink salt]], and two cups of cabbage or kale.<ref name=buzz1 /> The recipe calls for the ingredients to then be pur\u00e9ed in a blender, poured into a glass jar, covered, and left to ferment at room temperature for three days.<ref name=buzz1 /> Jillian Mai Thi Epperly, the creator of Jilly Juice, has claimed that salt is a \"positive element\" for the [[immune system]], and that cabbage contains important [[probiotic]]s and nutrients.<ref name=nzherald>{{cite web|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/lifestyle/news/article.cfm?c_id=6&objectid=12138355|title='Poop cult' leader 'can't be held accountable' for followers death|last=Rahhal|first=Natalie|date=October 7, 2018|work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]|access-date=January 5, 2020}}</ref> She has recommended that individuals start consuming two cups of Jilly Juice per day, and increasing their consumption of it to up to 16 cups a day or a gallon a day.<ref name=buzz1 /><ref name=newsweek /><ref name=exposing>{{cite book|last=Epperly|first=Jillian Mai Thi|date=2017|title=Candida: Weaponized Fungus Mainstreaming Mutancy|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/1NILL2O7UiJTdRPvb1ZbjK9pXkntjL0hg/view|publisher=|page=|isbn=|access-date=January 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nProponents of Jilly Juice have claimed that a variety of illnesses and conditions are the result of ''[[Candida (fungus)|Candida]]'', a [[yeast]] which they claim attracts parasites in one's body.<ref name=buzz1 /><ref name=buzz2 /> According to Epperly, an abundance of ''Candida'' in the body can cause harmful bacteria to multiply, create holes in the [[intestine]], and allow toxins from food to enter one's bloodstream\u2014she refers to this process as \"[[leaky gut syndrome]]\",<ref name=exposing /> which is a hypothetical and medically unrecognized condition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/leaky-gut-syndrome/|title=\"Leaky gut syndrome\" - NHS|publisher=[[National Health Service]]|access-date=January 6, 2020}}</ref> Epperly recommends a restricted diet supplemented by consuming large quantities of Jilly Juice, which supposedly removes ''Candida'' and parasites from one's body by inducing [[diarrhea]] (these bouts of diarrhea have been referred to by Jilly Juice advocates as \"waterfalls\").<ref name=buzz1 /><ref name=buzz2 />\n\nAlong with supposedly expunging ''Candida'' and parasites from one's body, Jilly Juice has been claimed to be able to cure [[autism]],<ref name=newsweek /> [[cancer]],<ref name=nzherald /> and [[psoriasis]],<ref name=metro /> as well as [[Limb regeneration|regenerate missing limbs]],<ref name=metro /><ref name=nzherald /> impede or reverse the effects of aging,<ref name=buzz1 /> and \"cure\" [[homosexuality]].<ref name=metro /><ref name=newsweek />\n\n==Efficacy==\nDrinking Jilly Juice is ineffective in treating ailments, and can cause serious harm\u2014including extreme [[dehydration]] and [[salt poisoning]]\u2014or death due to its high [[sodium]] content.<ref name=buzz1 /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbb.org/us/oh/canton/profile/health-and-medical-products/jilly-juice-0282-92019019/details|title=Jilly Juice - Business Details|website=[[Better Business Bureau]]|access-date=January 6, 2020}}</ref> [[Joseph A. Schwarcz]], director of [[McGill University]]'s [[Office for Science and Society]], has noted that the drink's dangerously high salt concentration can lead to [[hypertension]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://montrealgazette.com/opinion/columnists/the-right-chemistry-beware-of-self-proclaimed-health-experts|title=The Right Chemistry: Beware of self-proclaimed health experts|last=Schwarcz|first=Joseph|author-link=Joseph A. Schwarcz|date=June 1, 2018|work=[[Montreal Gazette]]|access-date=January 5, 2020}}</ref> Poor fermentation of the drink could also lead to ill effects.<ref name=buzz1 /> David Seres, director of medical nutrition at [[Columbia University Medical Center]], has called the claims of Jilly Juice proponents \"absolutely dangerous nonsense\".<ref name=buzz1 /><ref name=newsweek />\n\nIn 2018, the [[Federal Trade Commission]] (FTC) warned Epperly about claims made regarding Jilly Juice in a letter that stated: \"It is against the law to make health claims, whether directly or indirectly, through advertising or other means, without adequate scientific support at the time the claims are made, or to exaggerate the benefits of products or services you are promoting\".<ref name=buzz2 />\n\n==History==\n===Origins===\nJillian Mai Thi Epperly, the creator of Jilly Juice, was born in [[Vietnam]].<ref name=buzz1 /> She moved to the United States in May 1975 before the age of two, and was adopted by American parents.<ref name=exposing /> Her father worked in [[biotechnology]], which she claims helped her to realize that the [[pharmaceutical industry]] is working with doctors to [[Big Pharma conspiracy theory|keep consumers addicted to medication]].<ref name=buzz1 /> She met her husband online, then moved to Ohio to live with him.<ref name=buzz1 /> She developed [[premenstrual dysphoric disorder]] (PMDD), and after being exposed to [[pseudoscientific]] viewpoints and [[conspiracy theories]] such as the [[anti-vaccination]] movement and [[chemtrail]]s, she sought alternative methods to treat her PMDD.<ref name=buzz1 />\n\nIn her online research of various diseases, Epperly found that ''Candida'' or other fungi were \"always a factor\", and concluded that ''Candida'' was responsible for such diseases.<ref name=buzz1 /> Epperly began brewing and fermenting recipes for [[kombucha]] and pickles before deciding to brew fermented cabbage, with a significant salt content.<ref name=buzz1 /> The result, a concoction of water, salt, and fermented cabbage or kale which Epperly claims can treat a number of illnesses and conditions, was dubbed \"Jilly Juice\".<ref name=buzz1 />\n\n===Spread===\nEpperly began making Jilly Juice with cabbage and kale in October 2016, and by January 2017, she was posting videos related to the drink on her personal [[Facebook]] page.<ref name=buzz1 /> The videos garnered a following, leading to the creation of a Facebook group known as \"Exposing the Lies Candida: Weaponized Fungus Mainstreaming Mutancy\".<ref name=buzz1 /> Over the next few months, the group grew to include thousands of members.<ref name=buzz1 /> In the Facebook group, members would often post images of their bowel movements, comments about supposed parasites visible in said bowel movements, and videos of themselves drinking Jilly Juice, preparing Jilly Juice as an [[enema]], or giving Jilly Juice to young children and infants.<ref name=buzz1 />\n\nIn February 2017, after receiving backlash from groups opposed to the promotion and consumption of Jilly Juice, Epperly launched a website, Jillyjuice.com, and removed the Facebook group from public view.<ref name=buzz1 /> At its peak, the Facebook group had amassed over 58,000 members.<ref name=buzz1 /><ref name=nzherald /> Content on Jillyjuice.com, which includes private forums, can be accessed by paying $30 annually or $5 monthly.<ref name=buzz1 /><ref name=newsweek /> Epperly has also provided private phone consultations for $70 an hour.<ref name=buzz1 /><ref name=newsweek />\n\nIn May 2018, Epperly appeared on the American talk show ''[[Dr. Phil]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwlp.com/news/entertainment/dr-phil-jilly-juice-claims-to-cure-cancer-regrow-missing-limbs-reverse-aging/|title=Dr. Phil \u2013 \"Jilly Juice: Claims to cure cancer, regrow missing limbs, reverse aging\"|date=May 22, 2018|website=[[WWLP.com]]|access-date=January 5, 2019}}</ref> The show's host, [[Phil McGraw]], called Epperly's claims regarding Jilly Juice \"outrageous\".<ref name=metro />\n\n===Death of Bruce Wilmot===\nIn the summer of 2017, Bruce Wilmot, who was diagnosed with [[Stage four cancer|stage four]] [[pancreatic cancer]], began taking Jilly Juice.<ref name=nzherald /> Wilmot's daughter Taylor described him as \"emaciated\", and stated that he \"was drinking so much of it, he was basically starving himself. It was all coming out as diarrhea.\"<ref name=buzz1 />\n\nOn July 20, 2017, about a month after he began drinking Jilly Juice, Bruce Wilmot died.<ref name=buzz1 /><ref name=nzherald /> Epperly responded to his death in a video by saying that Wilmot did not consume enough Jilly Juice, stating that he \"really should have kept going\", and that his medications, his consumption of [[pineapple juice]], or the medical industry may have contributed to his death.<ref name=buzz1 /><ref name=nzherald /> Epperly later wrote that she \"can't be held accountable\" for deaths resulting from the consumption of Jilly Juice, and that \"[[correlation does not mean causation]].\"<ref name=nzherald />\n\n==Backlash==\nAfter Epperly's Facebook group grew in popularity, several other Facebook groups were created which opposed her and her followers' claims regarding Jilly Juice. A movement of Jilly Juice opponents, which has been described as \"anti-juice\", \"anti-Jillian\", and \"anti-Epperly\", has itself accrued thousands of adherents.<ref name=buzz1 /> Petitions on [[Change.org]] calling for Epperly and Jilly Juice to be banned from social media have also been created,<ref name=buzz1 /> and anti-Epperly advocates have reported her false health claims to the [[Food and Drug Administration]], the FTC, the State Medical Board of Ohio, and the [[Ohio Attorney General|Ohio Attorney General's Office]].<ref name=buzz2 /><ref name=newsweek />\n\n==See also==\n* [[Detoxification (alternative medicine)]]\n* [[Hypernatremia]]\n* [[Rope worms]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.jillyjuice.com/ Official website]\n\n[[Category:Alternative detoxification]]\n[[Category:Alternative medicine]]\n[[Category:Fermented drinks]]\n", "name_user": "2601:248:5401:130:ecc9:4fae:7e83:4b7a", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jilly_Juice"}
{"title_page": "R\u00f3bert G\u00f6nczi", "text_new": "{{short description|Hungarian boxer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = R\u00f3bert G\u00f6nczi\n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = Hungarian\n| sport          = [[Boxing]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1951|10|29|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[T\u00f6r\u00f6kb\u00e1lint]], Hungary\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|2000|11|30|1951|10|29|df=yes}}\n| death_place    = [[Kecskem\u00e9t]], Hungary\n}}\n\n'''R\u00f3bert G\u00f6nczi''' (29 October 1951 &ndash; 30 November 2000) was a Hungarian [[boxing|boxer]]. He competed in the [[Boxing at the 1980 Summer Olympics \u2013 Featherweight|men's featherweight]] event at the [[1980 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/go/robert-gonczi-1.html |title=R\u00f3bert G\u00f6nczi Olympic Results |accessdate=25 December 2018}}</ref> At the 1980 Summer Olympics, he lost to [[Titi Cercel]] of Romania.<ref name=\"SportsRef\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gonczi, Robert}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:2000 deaths]]\n[[Category:Hungarian male boxers]]\n[[Category:Olympic boxers of Hungary]]\n[[Category:Boxers at the 1980 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:People from T\u00f6r\u00f6kb\u00e1lint]]\n{{Hungary-boxing-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Hungarian boxer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = R\u00f3bert G\u00f6nczi\n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = Hungarian\n| sport          = [[Boxing]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1951|10|29|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[T\u00f6r\u00f6kb\u00e1lint]], Hungary\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|2000|11|30|1951|10|29|df=yes}}\n| death_place    = Kecskem\u00e9t, Hungary\n}}\n\n'''R\u00f3bert G\u00f6nczi''' (29 October 1951 &ndash; 30 November 2000) was a Hungarian [[boxing|boxer]]. He competed in the [[Boxing at the 1980 Summer Olympics \u2013 Featherweight|men's featherweight]] event at the [[1980 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/go/robert-gonczi-1.html |title=R\u00f3bert G\u00f6nczi Olympic Results |accessdate=25 December 2018}}</ref> At the 1980 Summer Olympics, he lost to [[Titi Cercel]] of Romania.<ref name=\"SportsRef\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gonczi, Robert}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:2000 deaths]]\n[[Category:Hungarian male boxers]]\n[[Category:Olympic boxers of Hungary]]\n[[Category:Boxers at the 1980 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:People from T\u00f6r\u00f6kb\u00e1lint]]\n{{Hungary-boxing-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Darwinek", "label": "safe", "comment": "link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/R%C3%B3bert_G%C3%B6nczi"}
{"title_page": "AussieBum", "text_new": "{{Advert|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=July 2013}}\n{{lowercase|aussieBum}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = aussieBum\n| logo = AussieBum logo.svg\n| logo_size = 175px\n| type = Private\n| foundation = 2001\n| founder = Sean Ashby\n| location_city = Sydney\n| location_country = Australia\n| area_served = Worldwide\n| industry = Fashion\n| products = Men's [[swimwear]], [[underwear]], and clothing\n| homepage = [http://www.aussiebum.com/ aussiebum.com]\n| footnotes = \n}}\n\n'''aussieBum''' is an Australian men's [[swimwear]] and [[underwear]] manufacturer.\n\nSome aussieBum underwear and swimwear is manufactured in Sydney's inner west. 95% of aussieBum products are manufactured in Australia All products are designed and despatched from Sydney, with the business run completely out of the company's headquarters in the suburb of [[Leichhardt, New South Wales|Leichhardt]].\n\n==Marketing==\nThe company has no sales representatives overseas but relies on the strength of the company website. Australian sales make up only 10% of its business. The company has a broad reach for a business run entirely via the Web, with no shop front and minimal packing staff.<ref name=\"International Herald Tribune\">{{cite web|author=International Herald Tribune |title=Aussiebum: Down Under designs in more ways than one |url=http://www.iht.com/articles/2008/01/21/style/raus.php |date=2008-01-21 |accessdate=2008-05-23 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080529033948/http://www.iht.com/articles/2008/01/21/style/raus.php |archivedate=29 May 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe brand retails in some of the biggest department stores in the world such as [[Selfridges]], [[Harrods]] and [[House of Fraser]] in the UK, [[Printemps]] in Paris, [[KaDeWe]] in Berlin, and [[Harvey Nichols]] in Dubai, as well as in small boutiques in various cities around the world. aussieBum's [[online shopping|online store]] ships to more than 150 countries with free delivery.<ref>{{cite news|author=Daily Telegraph |title=Wonderbra for men 'enhances' |url=http://www.news.com.au/story/0,23599,20693132-2,00.html |date=2006-11-03 |accessdate=2007-04-18 |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=UK |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071228224340/http://www.news.com.au/story/0%2C23599%2C20693132-2%2C00.html |archivedate=28 December 2007 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n[[File:AussieBum-ShearingRams.jpg|thumb|230px|aussieBum's version of ''[[Shearing the Rams]]'']]\nAussieBum promotes their products on various social media platforms such as [[Facebook]] and [[Twitter]]. The brand has a popular online following with the ''aussieBum'' being the 7th most popular search term in Australia.<ref name=\"International Herald Tribune\" /> \n\nThe brand uses a distinctly cheeky advertising style, such as remaking the Australian painting ''[[Shearing the Rams]]'' with muscle-bound men shearing sheep in just their underwear.<ref>{{cite news|author=Byrnes, Holly|title=Daily Telegraph: Shear art attack|url=http://www.news.com.au/dailytelegraph/story/0,22049,20500041-5006009,00.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071228220414/http://www.news.com.au/dailytelegraph/story/0,22049,20500041-5006009,00.html |archive-date=2007-12-28 |date=2006-09-30|accessdate=2019-10-25 |url-status=dead |work=The Daily Telegraph|location=AU}}</ref>\n\nCelebrities including [[Ewan McGregor]], [[Billy Connolly]], and [[Daniel Radcliffe]] are fans of aussieBum. Soccer superstar and men's fashion trendsetter [[David Beckham]] has also appeared in the brand.<ref>{{cite news|author=AAP|title=The Age: Bums rush|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/fashion/bums-rush/2005/10/20/1129401354721.html|date=2005-10-20|accessdate=2007-03-13 | location=Melbourne}}</ref>\n\nAussieBum swimwear has been featured in music video clips ''Slow'' by [[Kylie Minogue]] and ''SuperMartX\u00e9 VIP''\n\nIn 2011, during the first episode of [[The Celebrity Apprentice Australia]], director Sean Ashby gave $50,000 to charity when politician [[Pauline Hanson]] washed his car wearing aussieBum underwear, plus an additional $10,000 for [[Deni Hines]] to sing the national anthem.<ref>{{cite news|author=Christie, Joel|title=AussieBum gives Pauline Hanson $50,000 to strip to her underwear in Celebrity Apprentice car wash|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/sydney-confidential/pauline-hanson-strips-down-to-her-underwear-for-60000-car-wash-in-celebrity-apprentice-at-crystal-car-wash-bondi/story-e6frewz0-1226137028918|date=2011-09-14|accessdate=2011-12-15|work=Sydney Confidential The Daily Telegraph|location=AU}}</ref>\n\n==Products==\n[[File:AussieBum Undies in ice blue.jpg|thumb|200px|aussieBum men's [[briefs]], ''Ice Blue'' in colour]]\n[[File:Wonderjock.jpg|thumb|200px|aussieBum men's [[Jockstrap]], with the ''Wonderjock Technology'']]\n\n===Wonderjock===\nIn November 2006, the Wonderjock was launched in the aussieBum underwear lines. Wonderjocks have been designed to ''lift'' and ''enhance'' a man's \"package\", through the use of a fabric cup used to protrude everything out instead of just down. 50,000 pairs of the new underwear were sold in the first seven days of being released.<ref>{{cite news|author=Daily Telegraph|title=Daily Telegraph: Market grows for under wonder|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/internetNews/idUSSYD17865120061102|date=2006-11-01|accessdate=2007-04-18 | work=Reuters}}</ref> \n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Companies|Fashion|Australia}}\n{{commons category|AussieBum}}\n*[[List of swimwear brands]]\n*[[Speedo (suit style)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{men's undergarments}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:aussieBum}}\n[[Category:Clothing brands of Australia]]\n[[Category:Swimwear manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Swimwear brands]]\n[[Category:Underwear brands]]\n[[Category:Sportswear brands]]\n[[Category:Surfwear brands]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies based in Sydney]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 2001]]\n[[Category:2001 establishments in Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Advert|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=July 2013}}\n{{lowercase|aussieBum}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = aussieBum\n| logo = AussieBum logo.svg\n| logo_size = 175px\n| type = Private\n| foundation = 2001\n| founder = Sean Ashby\n| location_city = Sydney\n| location_country = Australia\n| area_served = Worldwide\n| industry = Fashion\n| products = Men's [[swimwear]], [[underwear]], and clothing\n| homepage = [http://www.aussiebum.com/ aussiebum.com]\n| footnotes = \n}}\n\n'''aussieBum''' is an Australian men's [[swimwear]] and [[underwear]] manufacturer.\n\nSome aussieBum underwear and swimwear is manufactured in Sydney's inner west. A growing number of aussieBum products are manufactured overseas in China<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aussiebum.com/mens/underwear/trunk/bodystretch-army/4680|language=en|access-date=2019-11-29|website=www.aussiebum.com|title=Bodystretch Army/Green/Trunk}}</ref>, Bangladesh<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aussiebum.com/t_shirts/longline-tank-apollo/3554|title=Longline Tank - Apollo|website=www.aussiebum.com|language=en|access-date=2017-04-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170421091702/http://www.aussiebum.com/t_shirts/longline-tank-apollo/3554|archive-date=21 April 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>, Thailand<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aussiebum.com/t_shirts/drylite-surf-short-red/3634|title=Drylite Surf Short - Red|website=www.aussiebum.com|language=en|access-date=2017-04-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170421000940/http://www.aussiebum.com/t_shirts/drylite-surf-short-red/3634|archive-date=21 April 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>, and Vietnam<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aussiebum.com/t_shirts/chino-short-king/3566|title=Chino short - King|website=www.aussiebum.com|language=en|access-date=2017-04-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170421091832/http://www.aussiebum.com/t_shirts/chino-short-king/3566|archive-date=21 April 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>. All products are designed and despatched from Sydney, with the business run completely out of the company's headquarters in the suburb of [[Leichhardt, New South Wales|Leichhardt]].\n\n==Marketing==\nThe company has no sales representatives overseas but relies on the strength of the company website. Australian sales make up only 10% of its business. The company has a broad reach for a business run entirely via the Web, with no shop front and minimal packing staff.<ref name=\"International Herald Tribune\">{{cite web|author=International Herald Tribune |title=Aussiebum: Down Under designs in more ways than one |url=http://www.iht.com/articles/2008/01/21/style/raus.php |date=2008-01-21 |accessdate=2008-05-23 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080529033948/http://www.iht.com/articles/2008/01/21/style/raus.php |archivedate=29 May 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe brand retails in some of the biggest department stores in the world such as [[Selfridges]], [[Harrods]] and [[House of Fraser]] in the UK, [[Printemps]] in Paris, [[KaDeWe]] in Berlin, and [[Harvey Nichols]] in Dubai, as well as in small boutiques in various cities around the world. aussieBum's [[online shopping|online store]] ships to more than 150 countries with free delivery.<ref>{{cite news|author=Daily Telegraph |title=Wonderbra for men 'enhances' |url=http://www.news.com.au/story/0,23599,20693132-2,00.html |date=2006-11-03 |accessdate=2007-04-18 |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=UK |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071228224340/http://www.news.com.au/story/0%2C23599%2C20693132-2%2C00.html |archivedate=28 December 2007 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n[[File:AussieBum-ShearingRams.jpg|thumb|230px|aussieBum's version of ''[[Shearing the Rams]]'']]\nAussieBum promotes their products on various social media platforms such as [[Facebook]] and [[Twitter]]. The brand has a popular online following with the ''aussieBum'' being the 7th most popular search term in Australia.<ref name=\"International Herald Tribune\" /> \n\nThe brand uses a distinctly cheeky advertising style, such as remaking the Australian painting ''[[Shearing the Rams]]'' with muscle-bound men shearing sheep in just their underwear.<ref>{{cite news|author=Byrnes, Holly|title=Daily Telegraph: Shear art attack|url=http://www.news.com.au/dailytelegraph/story/0,22049,20500041-5006009,00.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071228220414/http://www.news.com.au/dailytelegraph/story/0,22049,20500041-5006009,00.html |archive-date=2007-12-28 |date=2006-09-30|accessdate=2019-10-25 |url-status=dead |work=The Daily Telegraph|location=AU}}</ref>\n\nCelebrities including [[Ewan McGregor]], [[Billy Connolly]], and [[Daniel Radcliffe]] are fans of aussieBum. Soccer superstar and men's fashion trendsetter [[David Beckham]] has also appeared in the brand.<ref>{{cite news|author=AAP|title=The Age: Bums rush|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/fashion/bums-rush/2005/10/20/1129401354721.html|date=2005-10-20|accessdate=2007-03-13 | location=Melbourne}}</ref>\n\nAussieBum swimwear has been featured in music video clips ''Slow'' by [[Kylie Minogue]] and ''SuperMartX\u00e9 VIP''\n\nIn 2011, during the first episode of [[The Celebrity Apprentice Australia]], director Sean Ashby gave $50,000 to charity when politician [[Pauline Hanson]] washed his car wearing aussieBum underwear, plus an additional $10,000 for [[Deni Hines]] to sing the national anthem.<ref>{{cite news|author=Christie, Joel|title=AussieBum gives Pauline Hanson $50,000 to strip to her underwear in Celebrity Apprentice car wash|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/sydney-confidential/pauline-hanson-strips-down-to-her-underwear-for-60000-car-wash-in-celebrity-apprentice-at-crystal-car-wash-bondi/story-e6frewz0-1226137028918|date=2011-09-14|accessdate=2011-12-15|work=Sydney Confidential The Daily Telegraph|location=AU}}</ref>\n\n==Products==\n[[File:AussieBum Undies in ice blue.jpg|thumb|200px|aussieBum men's [[briefs]], ''Ice Blue'' in colour]]\n[[File:Wonderjock.jpg|thumb|200px|aussieBum men's [[Jockstrap]], with the ''Wonderjock Technology'']]\n\n===Wonderjock===\nIn November 2006, the Wonderjock was launched in the aussieBum underwear lines. Wonderjocks have been designed to ''lift'' and ''enhance'' a man's \"package\", through the use of a fabric cup used to protrude everything out instead of just down. 50,000 pairs of the new underwear were sold in the first seven days of being released.<ref>{{cite news|author=Daily Telegraph|title=Daily Telegraph: Market grows for under wonder|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/internetNews/idUSSYD17865120061102|date=2006-11-01|accessdate=2007-04-18 | work=Reuters}}</ref> \n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Companies|Fashion|Australia}}\n{{commons category|AussieBum}}\n*[[List of swimwear brands]]\n*[[Speedo (suit style)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{men's undergarments}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:aussieBum}}\n[[Category:Clothing brands of Australia]]\n[[Category:Swimwear manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Swimwear brands]]\n[[Category:Underwear brands]]\n[[Category:Sportswear brands]]\n[[Category:Surfwear brands]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies based in Sydney]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 2001]]\n[[Category:2001 establishments in Australia]]\n", "name_user": "61.69.255.54", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(correct the infor: products are 95% made in AUS)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AussieBum"}
{"title_page": "Vegan nutrition", "text_new": "[[File:Vegetarian diet.jpg|thumb|A variety of vegan foods includes fruits, vegetables and nuts.]]\n\n'''Vegan nutrition''' refers to the [[nutritional]] and [[human health]] aspects of [[vegan]] diets. A well-planned, balanced vegan diet is suitable to meet all recommendations for nutrients in every stage of human life.<ref name=\"melina\">{{cite journal | last=Melina | first=Vesanto | last2=Craig | first2=Winston | last3=Levin | first3=Susan | title=Position of the Academy of Nutrition and Dietetics: Vegetarian Diets | journal=Journal of the Academy of Nutrition and Dietetics | volume=115 | issue=5 | date=1 May 2015 | issn=2212-2672 | pmid=27886704 | doi=10.1016/j.jand.2016.09.025 | pages=1970\u20131980 | url=https://vegstudies.univie.ac.at/fileadmin/user_upload/inst_ethik_wiss_dialog/JAND_2015.05_Position_of_the_academy_of_nutrition_and_dietetics_vegetarian_diets..pdf | access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref> Vegan diets tend to be higher in [[dietary fiber]], [[magnesium]], [[Folate|folic acid]], [[vitamin C]], [[vitamin E]], [[iron]], and [[phytochemical]]s; and lower in [[Dietary energy supply|dietary energy]], [[saturated fat]], [[cholesterol]], [[Omega-3 fatty acid|long-chain omega-3 fatty acids]], [[vitamin D]], [[calcium]], [[zinc]], and [[Vitamin B12|vitamin B<sub>12</sub>]].<ref name=CraigMay2009>{{cite journal |last1=Craig |first1=Winston J |title=Health effects of vegan diets |journal=The American Journal of Clinical Nutrition |date=May 2009 |volume=89 |issue=5 |pages=1627S\u20131633S |doi=10.3945/ajcn.2009.26736N |pmid=19279075 |quote=Vegan diets are usually higher in dietary fiber, magnesium, folic acid, vitamins C and E, iron, and phytochemicals, and they tend to be lower in calories, saturated fat and cholesterol, long-chain n\u20133 (omega-3) fatty acids, vitamin D, calcium, zinc, and vitamin B-12.&nbsp;... A vegan diet appears to be useful for increasing the intake of protective nutrients and phytochemicals and for minimizing the intake of dietary factors implicated in several chronic diseases.|doi-access=free }}</ref> Preliminary evidence from [[Epidemiology|epidemiological research]] indicates that a vegan diet may lower the risk of [[cancer]].<ref name=\"Dinu\">{{cite journal | last=Dinu | first=Monica | last2=Abbate | first2=Rosanna | last3=Gensini | first3=Gian Franco | last4=Casini | first4=Alessandro | last5=Sofi | first5=Francesco | title=Vegetarian, vegan diets and multiple health outcomes: A systematic review with meta-analysis of observational studies | journal=Critical Reviews in Food Science and Nutrition | volume=57 | issue=17 | date=6 February 2016 | issn=1040-8398 | pmid=26853923 | doi=10.1080/10408398.2016.1138447 | pages=3640\u20133649| url=https://flore.unifi.it/bitstream/2158/1079985/4/Vegetarian%2c%20vegan%20diets%20and%20multiple%20he...meta-analysis%20of%20observational%20studies.pdf | hdl=2158/1079985 }}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n\nVegan diets, compared to standard diets, tend to be higher in [[dietary fibre]], [[magnesium]], [[folic acid]], [[vitamin C]], [[vitamin E]], and [[iron]], and lower in calories, saturated fat, cholesterol, long-chain [[omega-3 fatty acid]]s, vitamin D, calcium, zinc, and vitamin B<sub>12</sub>.<ref name=Craig>Craig, Winston J. [http://www.ajcn.org/content/89/5/1627S.long \"Health effects of vegan diets\"], ''The American Journal of Clinical Nutrition'', 89(5), May 2009, pp. 1627S\u20131633S (review article).</ref> Because plant foods do not provide vitamin B<sub>12</sub> (which is produced by [[microorganisms]] such as [[bacteria]]), researchers agree that those on a vegan diet should eat foods fortified with B<sub>12</sub> or take a [[dietary supplement]].<ref name=melina/><ref name=B12>[[Reed Mangels|Mangels, Reed]]; Messina, Virginia; and Messina, Mark. \"Vitamin B<sub>12</sub> (Cobalamin),\" ''The Dietitian's Guide to Vegetarian Diets''. Jones & Bartlett Learning, 2011, [https://books.google.com/books?id=eJ10HoYQ2woC&pg=PA181 pp. 181\u2013192].\n*Mangels, Reed. [http://www.vrg.org/nutrition/b12.htm \"Vitamin B<sub>12</sub> in the Vegan Diet\"], Vegetarian Resource Group, accessed December 17, 2012: \"Vitamin B<sub>12</sub> is needed for cell division and blood formation. Neither plants nor animals make vitamin B<sub>12</sub>. Bacteria are responsible for producing vitamin B<sub>12</sub>. Animals get their vitamin B<sub>12</sub> from eating foods contaminated with vitamin B<sub>12</sub> and then the animal becomes a source of vitamin B<sub>12</sub>. Plant foods do not contain vitamin B<sub>12</sub> except when they are contaminated by microorganisms or have vitamin B<sub>12</sub> added to them. Thus, vegans need to look to fortified foods or supplements to get vitamin B<sub>12</sub> in their diet.\"\n*[http://ods.od.nih.gov/factsheets/VitaminB12-HealthProfessional/ \"Vitamin B<sub>12</sub>\"], Office of Dietary Supplements, National Institutes of Health, accessed December 17, 2012.\n*Norris, Jack. [http://www.veganhealth.org/articles/vitaminb12 \"Vitamin B<sub>12</sub>: Are you getting it?\"], Vegan Outreach, July 26, 2006: \"Contrary to the many rumors, there are no reliable, unfortified plant sources of vitamin B<sub>12</sub> ... [There is an] overwhelming consensus in the mainstream nutrition community, as well as among vegan health professionals, that vitamin B<sub>12</sub> fortified foods or supplements are necessary for the optimal health of vegans, and even vegetarians in many cases. Luckily, vitamin B<sub>12</sub> is made by bacteria such that it does not need to be obtained from animal products.\"</ref>\n\n==Nutrition==\n\nThe American [[Academy of Nutrition and Dietetics]] (formerly known as the ''American Dietetic Association''), [[Dietitians of Canada]] and the [[British Dietetic Association]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bda.uk.com/foodfacts/vegetarianfoodfacts.pdf|title=Vegetarian Diets Food Facts Sheet|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090206044823/http://bda.uk.com/foodfacts/vegetarianfoodfacts.pdf|archive-date=2009-02-06|url-status=dead|access-date=18 September 2017}}</ref> state that well-planned vegan diets can meet all human nutrient requirements and are appropriate for all stages of life, including during [[pregnancy]], [[lactation]], [[infant|infancy]], [[childhood]], and [[adolescence]],<ref name=melina/> while the German Society for Nutrition does not recommend vegan diets for children, adolescents, or during pregnancy and [[breastfeeding]].<ref name=GermanyDGE>{{cite journal|authors=Richter M, Boeing H, Gr\u00fcnewald-Funk D, Heseker H, Kroke A, Leschik-Bonnet E, Oberritter H, Strohm D, Watzl B for the German Nutrition Society (DGE)|title=Vegan diet. Position of the German Nutrition Society (DGE)|journal=Ernahrungs Umschau|volume=63|issue=4|pages=92\u2013102. Erratum in: 63(05): M262|date=12 April 2016|doi=10.4455/eu.2016.021|url=https://www.ernaehrungs-umschau.de/fileadmin/Ernaehrungs-Umschau/pdfs/pdf_2016/04_16/EU04_2016_Special_DGE_eng_final.pdf}}{{open access}}</ref> The American Academy of Nutrition and Dietetics adds that well-planned vegan diets are also appropriate for older adults and athletes, and that vegan diets may reduce the risk of certain health conditions, such as cancer.<ref name=melina/>\n\nSpecial attention may be necessary to ensure that a vegan diet will provide adequate amounts of [[vitamin B12|vitamin B<sub>12</sub>]], omega-3 fatty acids, vitamin D, calcium, iodine, iron, and zinc.<ref name=melina/><ref name=\"andjrnl.org\"/> These nutrients may be available in plant foods, with the exception of vitamin B<sub>12</sub>, which can be obtained only from B<sub>12</sub>-fortified vegan foods or supplements. [[Iodine]] may also require supplementation, such as using iodized salt.<ref name=\"andjrnl.org\">[http://www.andjrnl.org/article/S2212-2672(16)31192-3/abstract#/article/S2212-2672(16)31192-3/fulltext (2016)(Full text) \"Position of the Academy of Nutrition and Dietetics: Vegetarian Diets.], J Acad Nutr Diet. 2016 Dec;116(12):1970-1980.</ref>\n\n== Nutritional deficiencies ==\n\n=== Vitamin B<sub>12</sub> ===\n{{further|Vitamin B12 deficiency}}\n[[File:Vegan food pyramid.svg|alt=|thumb|Vegan food pyramid based on suggestions from the [[American Dietetic Association]]]]\nVitamin B<sub>12</sub> is not made by plants or animals, but by bacteria that grow in soil, feces, dirty water, the intestines of animals or laboratories,<ref name=\"Fang\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Fang H, Kang J, Zhang D | title =Microbial production of vitamin 12: a review and future perspectives | journal = Microbial Cell Factories | volume = 16 | issue = 1 | pages = 15 | date = January 2017 | pmid = 28137297 | pmc = 5282855 | doi = 10.1186/s12934-017-0631-y }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Moore SJ, Warren MJ | title = The anaerobic biosynthesis of vitamin B<sub>12</sub>12 | journal = Biochemical Society Transactions | volume = 40 | issue = 3 | pages = 581\u20136 | date = June 2012 | pmid = 22616870 | doi = 10.1042/BST20120066 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Graham|first1=Ross M.|last2=Deery|first2=Evelyne|last3=Warren|first3=Martin J.|editor1-last=Warren|editor1-first=Martin J.|editor2-last=Smith|editor2-first=Alison G.|editor2-link=Alison Gail Smith | name-list-format = vanc |title=Tetrapyrroles Birth, Life and Death|date=2009|publisher=Springer-Verlag|location=New York, NY|isbn=978-0-387-78518-9|page=286|chapter=18: Vitamin B<sub>12</sub>: Biosynthesis of the Corrin Ring|doi=10.1007/978-0-387-78518-9_18}}</ref><ref name=BPE>{{cite news|last1=Rooke|first1=Jennifer| name-list-format = vanc |title=Do carnivores need Vitamin B<sub>12</sub> supplements?|url=http://baltimorepostexaminer.com/carnivores-need-vitamin-b12-supplements/2013/10/30|work=Baltimore Post Examiner|date=October 30, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Vitamin B<sub>12</sub>|url=http://www.dsm.com/markets/anh/en_US/Compendium/companion_animals/vitamin_B12.html|publisher=DSM|access-date=January 17, 2017}}</ref> so plant foods are not reliable sources of B<sub>12</sub>.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ods.od.nih.gov/factsheets/vitaminb12.asp |title=Dietary Supplement Fact Sheet: Vitamin B<sub>12</sub> |accessdate=2018-02-02 |quote= Strict vegetarians and vegans are at greater risk than lacto-ovo vegetarians and nonvegetarians of developing vitamin B<sub>12</sub> deficiency because natural food sources of vitamin B<sub>12</sub> are limited to animal foods. |publisher=[[National Institutes of Health]]: Office of Dietary Supplements }}</ref> The UK [[Vegan Society]], the Vegetarian Resource Group, and the [[Physicians Committee for Responsible Medicine]], among others, recommend that every vegan consume adequate B<sub>12</sub> either from [[food fortification|fortified foods]] or by taking a supplement.<ref name=\"watanabe20072\">{{cite journal|year=2007|title=Vitamin B<sub>12</sub> sources and bioavailability|url=|journal=Experimental Biology and Medicine |volume=232|issue=10|pages=1266\u20131274|doi=10.3181/0703-MR-67|pmid=17959839|last=Watanabe|first=F.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Vegan Society B<sub>12</sub> factsheet|url=http://www.vegansociety.com/food/nutrition/b12/|last=Walsh|first=Stephen|publisher=Vegan Society|accessdate=January 17, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080526073658/http://www.vegansociety.com/food/nutrition/b12/|archive-date=May 26, 2008|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"vrg.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vrg.org/nutrition/b12.htm |title=Vitamin B<sub>12</sub> in the Vegan Diet |accessdate=January 17, 2008|authorlink=Reed Mangels|last=Mangels|first=Reed|publisher=Vegetarian Resource Group}}</ref><ref name=\"B12PCRM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pcrm.org/health/diets/vegdiets/dont-vegetarians-have-trouble-getting-enough |title=Don't Vegetarians Have Trouble Getting Enough Vitamin B<sub>12</sub>? |accessdate=January 17, 2008 |publisher=[[Physicians Committee for Responsible Medicine]]}}</ref>\n\nVitamin B<sub>12</sub> deficiency is potentially extremely serious, leading to [[megaloblastic anemia]], nerve degeneration and irreversible neurological damage.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=C. |first1=Robert  | last2=Brown |first2=David  |url=http://www.aafp.org/afp/2003/0301/p979.html |title=Vitamin B<sub>12</sub> Deficiency |journal=American Family Physician  |volume=67 |issue=5 |pages=979\u2013986 |date=2003-03-01}}</ref>  Because B<sub>12</sub> is stored in large amounts in the liver, deficiency in adults may begin only years after adoption of a diet lacking B<sub>12</sub>.  For infants and young children who have not built up these stores, onset of B<sub>12</sub> deficiency can be faster and supplementation for vegan children is thus crucial.\n\nEvidence shows that vegans who are not taking vitamin B<sub>12</sub> supplements do not consume sufficient B<sub>12</sub> and often have abnormally low blood concentrations of vitamin B<sub>12</sub>.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1159/000012827 |title=Homocysteine Levels in Vegetarians versus Omnivores |year=2000 |last1=Kraj\u010dovi\u010dov\u00e1-Kudl\u00e1\u010dkov\u00e1 |first1=M. |last2=Bla\u017e\u00ed\u010dek |first2=P. |last3=Kop\u010dov\u00e1 |first3=J. |last4=B\u00e9derov\u00e1|first4=A. |last5=Babinsk\u00e1 |first5=K. |journal=Annals of Nutrition and Metabolism |volume=44 |issue=3 |pages=135\u20138 |pmid=11053901}}</ref>  This is because, unless fortified, plant foods do not contain reliable amounts of active vitamin B<sub>12</sub>. Vegans are advised to adopt one of the following dietary options:<ref>{{cite web|title = What Every Vegan Should Know About Vitamin B12|url = https://www.vegansociety.com/resources/nutrition-health/vitamins-minerals-and-more/vitamin-b12-your-key-facts/what-every-vegan-should-know-about-vitamin-b12|accessdate = 2015-08-05}}</ref> \n* Consume fortified foods 2-3 times per day to get at least 3 micrograms of vitamin B<sub>12</sub>,\n* or take 10 micrograms of B<sub>12</sub> as a supplement once per day\n* or take 2000 micrograms of B<sub>12</sub> as a supplement once per week\n\nB<sub>12</sub> is more efficiently absorbed in small regular doses, which explains why the quantity required rises so quickly as frequency goes down.\n\nThe US National Institutes of Health recommends B<sub>12</sub> intake in a range from 0.4 micrograms a day for infants, to 2.4 micrograms for adults, and up to 2.8 micrograms for nursing mothers.\n<ref>[https://ods.od.nih.gov/factsheets/VitaminB12-Consumer/#h2 \"Vitamin B<sub>12</sub>: Fact Sheet for Consumers\"] National Institutes of Health Office of Dietary Supplements (retrieved Dec 9, 2016)</ref>\nThe European Food Safety Authority set the Adequate Intake at 1.5 micrograms for infants, 4 micrograms for children and adults, and 4.5 and 5 micrograms during pregnancy and nursing.<ref>[http://www.efsa.europa.eu/en/efsajournal/pub/4150 \"Scientific Opinion on Dietary Reference Values for cobalamin (vitamin B<sub>12</sub>)\"] European Food Safety Authority Panel on Dietetic Products, Nutrition and Allergies. EFSA Journal 2015;13(7):4150 [64 pp.].</ref> These amounts can be obtained by eating B<sub>12</sub> fortified foods, which include some common breakfast cereals, soy milks, and meat analogues, as well as from common [[multivitamin]]s such as [[One-A-Day]]. Some of the fortified foods require only a single serving to provide the recommended B<sub>12</sub> amounts.\n<ref>[http://www.pcrm.org/health/diets/vegdiets/dont-vegetarians-have-trouble-getting-enough \"Don't Vegetarians Have Trouble Getting Enough Vitamin B<sub>12</sub>?\"] Physicians Committee for Responsible Medicine (retrieved Dec 9, 2016)</ref>\n\nOther B<sub>12</sub> fortified foods may include some almond milks, coconut milks, other plant milks, nutritional yeast, vegan mayonnaise, tofu, and various types and brands of vegan deli slices, burgers, and other veggie meats.\n\n=== Protein ===\n\n{{See also|Protein deficiency|Protein quality}}\n\nUpon digestion, all protein foods supply [[amino acid]]s. Varied intake of plant foods can meet human health needs for protein and amino acids.<ref name=melina/><ref name=\"andjrnl.org\"/> Foods high in protein in a vegan diet include [[legume]]s (such as beans and [[lentil]]s), nuts, seeds, and grains (such as oats, wheat, and [[quinoa]]).<ref name=melina/><ref name=\"healthscopemag\">{{cite web|url=https://www.healthscopemag.com/health-scope/plating-more-plant-based-protein/ |title=Plating More Plant-Based Protein |publisher=Healthscope Magazine |url-status=live |accessdate = 2015-08-15}}</ref>\n\n=== Omega-3 fatty acids ===\n[[File:Flax seeds.jpg|thumb|[[Flaxseed]]s are a rich source of ALA, the precursor to DHA and EPA, the [[omega-3 fatty acids]]]] \n[[File:English Walnuts.jpg|thumb|[[Walnuts]] are another rich source of ALA, the precursor to DHA and EPA, the [[omega-3 fatty acid|omega-3 oil]]s]]\n\nMajor vegan sources of the essential [[omega-3 fatty acid]] ALA include [[walnut]]s, [[flax|flaxseeds and flaxseed oil]], [[canola]] ([[rapeseed]]) oil, [[algae]] oil, [[hemp|hempseeds and hempseed oil]], [[olive oil]], and [[avocado]].<ref name=\"andjrnl.org\"/>\n\nDiets without seafood are lower in non-essential long-chain [[omega-3 fatty acid]]s like DHA and EPA. Short-term supplemental ALA has been shown to increase EPA levels, but not DHA levels, suggesting limited conversion of the intermediary EPA to DHA.<ref name=\"dha\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.plefa.2009.05.013 |title=DHA status of vegetarians |year=2009 |last1=Sanders |first1=Thomas A.B. |journal=Prostaglandins, Leukotrienes and Essential Fatty Acids |volume=81 |issue=2\u20133 |pmid=19500961 |pages=137\u201341}}</ref> DHA supplements derived from DHA-rich [[alga|microalgae]] are available, and the human body can also convert DHA to EPA.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Colette |last1=Bouchez |title=Good Fat, Bad Fat: The Facts About Omega-3 |url=http://women.webmd.com/features/omega-3-fatty-acids |website=[[WebMD]]}}</ref> Although omega-3 has previously been thought useful for helping alleviate [[dementia]], {{asof|2016|lc=yes}}, there is no good evidence of effectiveness.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Burckhardt M, Herke M, Wustmann T, Watzke S, Langer G, Fink A |title=Omega-3 fatty acids for the treatment of dementia |journal=Cochrane Database Syst Rev |volume=4 |issue= |pages=CD009002 |year=2016 |pmid=27063583 |doi=10.1002/14651858.CD009002.pub3 |type=Systematic review|pmc=7117565 }}</ref>\n\nWhile there is little evidence of adverse health or cognitive effects due to DHA deficiency in adult vegetarians or vegans, fetal and breast milk levels remain a concern.<ref name=\"dha\" /> EPA and DHA supplementation has been shown to reduce platelet aggregation in vegetarians, but a direct link to cardiovascular morbidity and mortality, which is already lower for vegetarians, has yet to be determined.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/S0049-3848(00)00313-3 |title=Cardiovascular Risk Factors in Vegetarians: Normalization of Hyperhomocysteinemia with Vitamin B<sub>12</sub> and Reduction of Platelet Aggregation with n-3 Fatty Acids |year=2000 |last1=Mezzano |first1=Diego |last2=Kosiel |first2=Karin |last3=Mart\u00ednez |first3=Carlos |last4=Cuevas |first4=Ada |last5=Panes |first5=Olga |last6=Aranda |first6=Eduardo |last7=Strobel |first7=Pablo |last8=P\u00e9rez |first8=Druso D |last9=Pereira |first9=Jaime |last10=Rozowski |first10=Jaime |last11=Leighton |first11=Federico |journal=[[Thrombosis Research]] |volume=100 |issue=3 |pages=153\u201360 |pmid=11108902|display-authors=9 }}</ref>\n\n=== Calcium ===\nIt is recommended that vegans eat three servings per day of a high-[[calcium]] food, such as [[Food fortification|fortified]] [[plant milk]]s, green leafy vegetables, seeds, [[tofu]], or other calcium-rich foods, and take a calcium supplement as necessary.<ref name=melina/><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Craig|first=Winston J|date=2009-03-11|title=Health effects of vegan diets|journal=The American Journal of Clinical Nutrition|language=en|volume=89|issue=5|pages=1627S\u20131633S|doi=10.3945/ajcn.2009.26736N|pmid=19279075|issn=0002-9165|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nMany studies have examined possible correlation between veganism, calcium intake, and bone health. The [[European Prospective Investigation into Cancer and Nutrition|EPIC-Oxford]] study suggested that vegans who consumed 525&nbsp;mg or less of calcium per day have an increased risk of bone fractures over meat eaters and vegetarians, but that vegans consuming more than 525&nbsp;mg/day had a risk of fractures similar to other groups. Overall, the entire group of vegans had a higher risk of fractures.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1038/sj.ejcn.1602659 |title=Comparative fracture risk in vegetarians and nonvegetarians in EPIC-Oxford |year=2007 |last1=Appleby |first1=P |last2=Roddam |first2=A |last3=Allen |first3=N |last4=Key |first4=T |journal=European Journal of Clinical Nutrition |volume=61 |issue=12 |pages=1400\u20136 |pmid=17299475|doi-access=free }}</ref> A 2009 study of bone density found the bone density of vegans was 94 percent that of omnivores, but deemed the difference clinically insignificant.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.3945/ajcn.2009.27521 |title=Effect of vegetarian diets on bone mineral density: A Bayesian meta-analysis |year=2009 |last1=Ho-Pham |first1=L. T |last2=Nguyen |first2=N. D |last3=Nguyen |first3=T. V |journal=American Journal of Clinical Nutrition |volume=90 |issue=4 |pages=943\u201350 |pmid=19571226|doi-access=free }}</ref> Another study in 2009 by the same researchers examined over 100 vegan post-menopausal women, and found that their diet had no adverse effect on bone mineral density (BMD) and no alteration in body composition.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1007/s00198-009-0916-z |title=Veganism, bone mineral density, and body composition: A study in Buddhist nuns |year=2009 |last1=Ho-Pham |first1=L. T. |last2=Nguyen |first2=P. L. T. |last3=Le |first3=T. T. T. |last4=Doan |first4=T. A. T. |last5=Tran |first5=N. T. |last6=Le |first6=T. A. |last7=Nguyen |first7=T. V. |journal=Osteoporosis International |volume=20 |issue=12 |pages=2087\u201393 |pmid=19350341}}</ref> Biochemist [[T. Colin Campbell]] suggested in ''[[The China Study]]'' (2005) that [[osteoporosis]] is linked to the consumption of animal protein because, unlike plant protein, animal protein increases the acidity of blood and tissues, which he believed was neutralized by calcium pulled from the bones resulting in [[hypercalciuria]]. Campbell wrote that his [[China-Oxford-Cornell Study on Dietary, Lifestyle and Disease Mortality Characteristics in 65 Rural Chinese Counties|China-Oxford-Cornell study]] of nutrition in the 1970s and 1980s found that, in rural China, \"where the animal to plant ratio [for protein] was about 10 percent, the fracture rate is only one-fifth that of the U.S.\"<ref>Campbell, T. Colin. [https://books.google.com/books?id=KgRR12F0RPAC&pg=PA205 ''The China Study'']. Benbella Books, 2006, pp. 205\u2013208.</ref>\n\nCalcium is one component of the most common type of human kidney stones, [[calcium oxalate]]. Some studies suggest that people who take [[dietary supplement|supplemental calcium]] have a higher risk of developing kidney stones, and these findings have been used as the basis for setting the [[Reference Daily Intake|recommended daily intake]] (RDI) for calcium in adults.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Brody |first1=Jane E. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/05/08/science/huge-study-of-diet-indicts-fat-and-meat.html |title=Huge Study Of Diet Indicts Fat And Meat |work=The New York Times |date=May 8, 1990}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Junshi |editor1-first=Chen |editor2-last=Campbell |editor2-first=T. Colin |editor3-last=Li |editor4-last=Peto |editor4-first=R. | displayeditors = 3|title=Diet, lifestyle, and mortality in China: a study of the characteristics of 65 Chinese counties |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=1990 |isbn=978-0-19-261843-6}}{{page needed|date=June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Byers |first1=Tim |url=http://aje.oxfordjournals.org/content/135/10/1180.extract |title=Book Reviews: Diet, lifestyle, and mortality in China: a study of the characteristics of 65 Chinese counties |journal=American Journal of Epidemiology |volume=135 |issue=10 |pages=1180\u20131 |date=1992-05-15|doi=10.1093/oxfordjournals.aje.a116219 }}</ref>\n\n=== Iodine ===\n\nOne study reported a \"potential danger of [[iodine]] deficiency disorders due to strict forms of vegetarian nutrition, especially when fruits and vegetables grown in soils with low [iodine] levels are ingested.\"<ref>{{cite journal |first1=Thomas |last1=Remer |first2=Annette |last2=Neubert |first3=Friedrich |last3=Manz |title=Increased risk of iodine deficiency with vegetarian nutrition |journal=British Journal of Nutrition |pmid=10341675 |year=1999 |volume=81 |issue=1 |pages=45\u20139 |doi=10.1017/s0007114599000136|doi-access=free }}</ref> Vegan diets typically require special attention for iodine, for which the only substantial and reliable vegan sources are sea vegetables, iodized salt and supplements. The iodine content of sea vegetables varies widely and may provide more than the recommended upper limit of iodine intake.<ref name=\"andjrnl.org\"/>\n\n=== Iron ===\nIt is recommended for vegans to eat iron-rich foods and vitamin C daily.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/bhcv2/bhcarticles.nsf/pages/iron_deficiency_adults?open|title=Iron deficiency\u2014adults|quote=High-risk groups such as vegetarians, adolescent girls and women athletes need to eat iron-rich foods each day (combined with foods that are high in vitamin C). ... Vegetarians who exclude all animal products from their diet may need almost twice as much dietary iron each day as non-vegetarians. Sources include dark green leafy vegetables\u2014such as spinach\u2014and raisins, nuts, seeds, beans, peas, and iron-fortified cereals, breads and pastas}}</ref> In several studies, vegans were not found to suffer from [[iron]]-deficiency any more than non-vegans.<ref>{{cite journal |pmid=12081822 |year=2002 |last1=Larsson |first1=CL |last2=Johansson |first2=GK |title=Dietary intake and nutritional status of young vegans and omnivores in Sweden |volume=76 |issue=1 |pages=100\u20136 |journal=The American Journal of Clinical Nutrition|doi=10.1093/ajcn/76.1.100 |doi-access=free }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Messina |first1=MJ |last2=Messina |first2=VL |title=The Dietitian's Guide to Vegetarian Diets: Issues and Applications |location=Gaithersburg, MD |publisher=Aspen Publishers |year=1996}}{{page needed|date=June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |pmid=8172127 |year=1994 |last1=Craig |first1=WJ |title=Iron status of vegetarians |volume=59 |issue=5 Suppl |pages=1233S\u20131237S |journal=The American Journal of Clinical Nutrition|doi=10.1093/ajcn/59.5.1233S }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |pmid=10479197 |year=1999 |last1=Ball |first1=MJ |last2=Bartlett |first2=MA |title=Dietary intake and iron status of Australian vegetarian women |volume=70 |issue=3 |pages=353\u20138 |journal=The American Journal of Clinical Nutrition|doi=10.1093/ajcn/70.3.353 |doi-access=free }}</ref> However, due to the low absorption rate on non-heme iron it is recommended to eat dark leafy greens (and other sources of iron) together with sources of Vitamin C.<ref>{{Cite journal|quote=The key role of ascorbic acid for the absorption of dietary nonheme iron is generally accepted. The reasons for its action are twofold: (1) the prevention of the formation of insoluble and unabsorbable iron compounds and (2) the reduction of ferric to ferrous iron, which seems to be a requirement for the uptake of iron into the mucosal cells.|title=The role of vitamin C in iron absorption|journal=International Journal for Vitamin and Nutrition Research. Supplement|volume=30|pages=103\u20138|pmid=2507689|year=1989|last1=Hallberg|first1=L|last2=Brune|first2=M|last3=Rossander|first3=L}}</ref> Iron supplementation should be taken at different times to other supplements with a 2+ [[valence (chemistry)]] such as calcium or magnesium, as they inhibit the absorption of iron.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=L\u00f6nnerdal |first1=B |title=Calcium and iron absorption--mechanisms and public health relevance. |journal=Int J Vitam Nutr Res |date=October 2010 |volume=90 |issue=4\u20135 |pages=293\u20139 |doi=10.1024/0300-9831/a000036 |pmid=21462112 }}</ref>\n\n=== Choline ===\n{{Importance section|date=January 2019}}\nDue to lack of evidence, no country has published a recommended daily intake for [[choline]], which is a vitamin-like essential nutrient.  The Australian, New Zealand, and European Union national nutrition bodies note there have been no reports of choline deficiency in the general population.<ref>{{citation|title=Nutrient Reference Values for Australia and New Zealand|url=https://www.nrv.gov.au/nutrients/choline|quote=Although choline is essential, there appear to have been no reports of deficiency in the general population. Deficiencies have been seen in experimental situations and also in total parenteral nutrition (Buchman et al. 1992, 1993, 1995, Chalwa et al. 1989, Shapira et al. 1986, Sheard et al. 1986).}}</ref> There are, however, Adequate Intakes such as the European Union's number of 400&nbsp;mg/day for adults, and the US's number of 425&nbsp;mg/day for adult non-pregnant women and 550&nbsp;mg/day for adult men.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ods.od.nih.gov/factsheets/Choline-HealthProfessional/|title=Choline|publisher=Office of Dietary Supplements, US National Institutes of Health|date=26 September 2018|accessdate=26 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nCholine deficiency, as created in lab conditions, can lead to health problems such as liver damage, a result of liver cells initiating programmed cell death (apoptosis), as well as an increase in neural tube defects in pregnant women.<ref name=\"Higdon\">{{cite web |last=Higdon |first=Jane |title=Choline |publisher=Linus Pauling Institute at Oregon State University |date=Nov 2003 |url=http://lpi.oregonstate.edu/infocenter/othernuts/choline/ |accessdate=3 March 2014}}</ref> In a study, 77% of men, 44% of premenopausal women, and 80% of postmenopausal women developed fatty liver or muscle damage due to choline deficiency, showing that subject characteristics regulate the dietary requirement.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Fischer |first=Leslie M. |last2=DaCosta |first2=Kerry A. |last3=Kwock |first3=Lester |last4=Stewart |first4=Paul W. |last5=Lu |first5=Tsui-Shan |last6=Stabler |first6=Sally P. |last7=Allen |first7=Robert H. |last8=Zeisel |first8=Steven H. |title=Sex and Menopausal Status Influence Human Dietary Requirements for the Nutrient Choline |journal=The American Journal of Clinical Nutrition |volume=85 |issue=5 |pages=1275\u20131285 |date=May 2007 |doi=10.1093/ajcn/85.5.1275 |pmid=17490963 |pmc=2435503 }}</ref>  There is also some evidence that choline is an anti-inflammatory as well, but further studies are needed to confirm/refute findings.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Paraskevi |first=Detopoulou |last2=Panagiotakos |first2=Demosthenes B. |last3=Antonopoulou |first3=Smaragdi |last4=Pitsavos |first4=Christos |last5=Stefanadis |first5=Christodoulos |title=Dietary Choline and Betaine Intakes in Relation to Concentrations of Inflammatory Markers in Healthy Adults: The ATTICA Study |journal=The American Journal of Clinical Nutrition |volume=87 |issue=2 |pages=424\u2013430 |date=5 Sep 2007 |doi=10.1093/ajcn/87.2.424 |pmid=18258634 |doi-access=free }}</ref> It is worth noting that many multivitamins do not contain the Adequate Intake of choline.<ref>{{cite journal |last=McCord |first=BreAnn |title=Multivitamins Lack Choline |place=Beloit College }}</ref>\n\nAlthough many animal products, like liver and egg, contain high amounts of choline (355&nbsp;mg/3 oz and 126&nbsp;mg/large egg, respectively), wheat germ (172&nbsp;mg/cup), brussel sprouts (63&nbsp;mg/cup), and broccoli (62&nbsp;mg/cup) are also good sources of choline.<ref name=\"Higdon\"/>  Other sources include soy lecithin, cauliflower, spinach, wheat germ, firm tofu, kidney beans, quinoa and amaranth.\n\n=== Vitamin D ===\nThe main function of vitamin D in the body is increased absorption of calcium, therefore it is good for the bones. It also connects with receptors in the prostate, the heart, blood vessels, muscles, [[endocrine gland]]s and others.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.health.harvard.edu/staying-healthy/vitamin-d-and-your-health-breaking-old-rules-raising-new-hopes |author=Harvard Men's Health Watch |title=Vitamin D and your health: Breaking old rules, raising new hopes |publisher=Harvard MEdical School |date=February 2007 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSunlight, fortified foods, and supplements, are the main sources of vitamin D for vegans. Humans produce [[vitamin D]] naturally in response to [[Ultraviolet|ultraviolet light]] (UV). Complete cloud cover reduces UV penetration by up to 50%, and outdoor shade reduces UV penetration by 60%. UV light penetrates the skin at wavelengths between 290 and 320 nanometers, where it is then converted into vitamin D3.<ref name=\"healthpro\">{{cite web|url=https://ods.od.nih.gov/factsheets/VitaminD-HealthProfessional/ |author=US National Institute of Health |title=Vitamin D Fact Sheet for Health Professionals |publisher=US National Institute of Health |url-status=live}}</ref> Vitamin D2 can be obtained from [[fungus|fungi]], such as [[mushroom]]s exposed to sun or industrial [[ultraviolet light]], offering a vegan choice for dietary or supplemental vitamin D.<ref name=usda-mush-light>{{cite web|author=Haytowitz DB|title=Vitamin D in mushrooms|url=https://www.ars.usda.gov/ARSUserFiles/80400525/Articles/AICR09_Mushroom_VitD.pdf|publisher=Nutrient Data Laboratory, US Department of Agriculture|accessdate=16 April 2018|date=2009}}</ref><ref name=\"keegan\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Keegan RJ, Lu Z, Bogusz JM, Williams JE, Holick MF | title = Photobiology of vitamin D in mushrooms and its bioavailability in humans | journal = Dermato-Endocrinology | volume = 5 | issue = 1 | pages = 165\u201376 | date = January 2013 | pmid = 24494050 | pmc = 3897585 | doi = 10.4161/derm.23321 }}</ref>\n\nAlthough vitamin D3 is produced in small amounts by [[lichen]]s or [[algae]] exposed to sunlight,<ref name=\"bjorn\">{{cite journal | last=Bj\u00f6rn | first=LO | last2=Wang | first2=T | title=Vitamin D in an ecological context. | journal=International Journal of Circumpolar Health | volume=59 | issue=1 | year=2000 | issn=1239-9736 | pmid=10850004 | pages=26\u201332}}</ref><ref name=\"japelt\">{{cite journal | last=J\u00e4pelt | first=Rie B. | last2=Jakobsen | first2=Jette | title=Vitamin D in plants: a review of occurrence, analysis, and biosynthesis | journal=Frontiers in Plant Science| volume=4 | pages=136 | year=2013 | issn=1664-462X | doi=10.3389/fpls.2013.00136 | pmid=23717318|pmc=3651966}}</ref> industrial production in commercial quantities is limited, and there are few supplement products as of 2019.<ref name=\"nutra\">{{cite web |author=Adi Menayang| title=AIDP: \"There is a significant market potential for vegan D3\" | publisher=NutraIngredients-USA, William Reed, Inc | date=29 April 2019 | url=https://www.nutraingredients-usa.com/Article/2019/04/29/AIDP-There-is-a-significant-market-potential-for-vegan-D3 | access-date=10 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe recommended daily allowance in vitamin D for adults under the age of 70 years old is between 600 and 4,000 [[international unit|IU]], and for adults over 70 years old, 800 to 4,000 IU.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dietitians.ca/getattachment/464f3006-0bb2-4f1a-a338-0b21d148bacb/FACTSHEET-Food-Sources-of-Vitamin-D.pdf.aspx |author=Detitians of Canada |title=Food Sources of Vitamin D |publisher=Dietitians of Canada |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nReports on exactly how much vitamin D is produced by exposure to sunlight are wild and varied, across the board.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Vegetarian nutrition]]\n* [[Nutrition]]\n* [[Raw veganism]]\n* [[Orthomolecular medicine|Nutritional medicine]]\n* ''[[The China Study]]'' from 2005\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Vegetarianism}}\n\n[[Category:Veganism]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Vegetarian diet.jpg|thumb|A variety of vegan foods includes fruits, vegetables and nuts.]]\n\n'''Vegan nutrition''' refers to the [[nutritional]] and [[human health]] aspects of [[vegan]] diets. A well-planned, balanced vegan diet is suitable to meet all recommendations for nutrients in every stage of human life.<ref name=\"melina\">{{cite journal | last=Melina | first=Vesanto | last2=Craig | first2=Winston | last3=Levin | first3=Susan | title=Position of the Academy of Nutrition and Dietetics: Vegetarian Diets | journal=Journal of the Academy of Nutrition and Dietetics | volume=115 | issue=5 | date=1 May 2015 | issn=2212-2672 | pmid=27886704 | doi=10.1016/j.jand.2016.09.025 | pages=1970\u20131980 | url=https://vegstudies.univie.ac.at/fileadmin/user_upload/inst_ethik_wiss_dialog/JAND_2015.05_Position_of_the_academy_of_nutrition_and_dietetics_vegetarian_diets..pdf | access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref> Vegan diets tend to be higher in [[dietary fiber]], [[magnesium]], [[Folate|folic acid]], [[vitamin C]], [[vitamin E]], [[iron]], and [[phytochemical]]s; and lower in [[Dietary energy supply|dietary energy]], [[saturated fat]], [[cholesterol]], [[Omega-3 fatty acid|long-chain omega-3 fatty acids]], [[vitamin D]], [[calcium]], [[zinc]], and [[Vitamin B12|vitamin B<sub>12</sub>]].<ref name=CraigMay2009>{{cite journal |last1=Craig |first1=Winston J |title=Health effects of vegan diets |journal=The American Journal of Clinical Nutrition |date=May 2009 |volume=89 |issue=5 |pages=1627S\u20131633S |doi=10.3945/ajcn.2009.26736N |pmid=19279075 |quote=Vegan diets are usually higher in dietary fiber, magnesium, folic acid, vitamins C and E, iron, and phytochemicals, and they tend to be lower in calories, saturated fat and cholesterol, long-chain n\u20133 (omega-3) fatty acids, vitamin D, calcium, zinc, and vitamin B-12.&nbsp;... A vegan diet appears to be useful for increasing the intake of protective nutrients and phytochemicals and for minimizing the intake of dietary factors implicated in several chronic diseases.|doi-access=free }}</ref> Preliminary evidence from [[Epidemiology|epidemiological research]] indicates that a vegan diet may lower the risk of [[cancer]].<ref name=\"Dinu\">{{cite journal | last=Dinu | first=Monica | last2=Abbate | first2=Rosanna | last3=Gensini | first3=Gian Franco | last4=Casini | first4=Alessandro | last5=Sofi | first5=Francesco | title=Vegetarian, vegan diets and multiple health outcomes: A systematic review with meta-analysis of observational studies | journal=Critical Reviews in Food Science and Nutrition | volume=57 | issue=17 | date=6 February 2016 | issn=1040-8398 | pmid=26853923 | doi=10.1080/10408398.2016.1138447 | pages=3640\u20133649| url=https://flore.unifi.it/bitstream/2158/1079985/4/Vegetarian%2c%20vegan%20diets%20and%20multiple%20he...meta-analysis%20of%20observational%20studies.pdf | hdl=2158/1079985 }}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n\nVegan diets, compared to standard diets, tend to be higher in [[dietary fibre]], [[magnesium]], [[folic acid]], [[vitamin C]], [[vitamin E]], and [[iron]], and lower in calories, saturated fat, cholesterol, long-chain [[omega-3 fatty acid]]s, vitamin D, calcium, zinc, and vitamin B<sub>12</sub>.<ref name=Craig>Craig, Winston J. [http://www.ajcn.org/content/89/5/1627S.long \"Health effects of vegan diets\"], ''The American Journal of Clinical Nutrition'', 89(5), May 2009, pp. 1627S\u20131633S (review article).</ref> Because plant foods do not provide vitamin B<sub>12</sub> (which is produced by [[microorganisms]] such as [[bacteria]]), researchers agree that those on a vegan diet should eat foods fortified with B<sub>12</sub> or take a [[dietary supplement]].<ref name=melina/><ref name=B12>[[Reed Mangels|Mangels, Reed]]; Messina, Virginia; and Messina, Mark. \"Vitamin B<sub>12</sub> (Cobalamin),\" ''The Dietitian's Guide to Vegetarian Diets''. Jones & Bartlett Learning, 2011, [https://books.google.com/books?id=eJ10HoYQ2woC&pg=PA181 pp. 181\u2013192].\n*Mangels, Reed. [http://www.vrg.org/nutrition/b12.htm \"Vitamin B<sub>12</sub> in the Vegan Diet\"], Vegetarian Resource Group, accessed December 17, 2012: \"Vitamin B<sub>12</sub> is needed for cell division and blood formation. Neither plants nor animals make vitamin B<sub>12</sub>. Bacteria are responsible for producing vitamin B<sub>12</sub>. Animals get their vitamin B<sub>12</sub> from eating foods contaminated with vitamin B<sub>12</sub> and then the animal becomes a source of vitamin B<sub>12</sub>. Plant foods do not contain vitamin B<sub>12</sub> except when they are contaminated by microorganisms or have vitamin B<sub>12</sub> added to them. Thus, vegans need to look to fortified foods or supplements to get vitamin B<sub>12</sub> in their diet.\"\n*[http://ods.od.nih.gov/factsheets/VitaminB12-HealthProfessional/ \"Vitamin B<sub>12</sub>\"], Office of Dietary Supplements, National Institutes of Health, accessed December 17, 2012.\n*Norris, Jack. [http://www.veganhealth.org/articles/vitaminb12 \"Vitamin B<sub>12</sub>: Are you getting it?\"], Vegan Outreach, July 26, 2006: \"Contrary to the many rumors, there are no reliable, unfortified plant sources of vitamin B<sub>12</sub> ... [There is an] overwhelming consensus in the mainstream nutrition community, as well as among vegan health professionals, that vitamin B<sub>12</sub> fortified foods or supplements are necessary for the optimal health of vegans, and even vegetarians in many cases. Luckily, vitamin B<sub>12</sub> is made by bacteria such that it does not need to be obtained from animal products.\"</ref>\n\n==Nutrition==\n\nThe American [[Academy of Nutrition and Dietetics]] (formerly known as the ''American Dietetic Association''), [[Dietitians of Canada]] and the [[British Dietetic Association]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bda.uk.com/foodfacts/vegetarianfoodfacts.pdf|title=Vegetarian Diets Food Facts Sheet|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090206044823/http://bda.uk.com/foodfacts/vegetarianfoodfacts.pdf|archive-date=2009-02-06|url-status=dead|access-date=18 September 2017}}</ref> state that well-planned vegan diets can meet all human nutrient requirements and are appropriate for all stages of life, including during [[pregnancy]], [[lactation]], [[infant|infancy]], [[childhood]], and [[adolescence]],<ref name=melina/> while the German Society for Nutrition does not recommend vegan diets for children, adolescents, or during pregnancy and [[breastfeeding]].<ref name=GermanyDGE>{{cite journal|authors=Richter M, Boeing H, Gr\u00fcnewald-Funk D, Heseker H, Kroke A, Leschik-Bonnet E, Oberritter H, Strohm D, Watzl B for the German Nutrition Society (DGE)|title=Vegan diet. Position of the German Nutrition Society (DGE)|journal=Ernahrungs Umschau|volume=63|issue=4|pages=92\u2013102. Erratum in: 63(05): M262|date=12 April 2016|doi=10.4455/eu.2016.021|url=https://www.ernaehrungs-umschau.de/fileadmin/Ernaehrungs-Umschau/pdfs/pdf_2016/04_16/EU04_2016_Special_DGE_eng_final.pdf}}{{open access}}</ref> The American Academy of Nutrition and Dietetics adds that well-planned vegan diets are also appropriate for older adults and athletes, and that vegan diets may reduce the risk of certain health conditions, such as cancer.<ref name=melina/>\n\nSpecial attention may be necessary to ensure that a vegan diet will provide adequate amounts of [[vitamin B12|vitamin B<sub>12</sub>]], omega-3 fatty acids, vitamin D, calcium, iodine, iron, and zinc.<ref name=melina/><ref name=\"andjrnl.org\"/> These nutrients may be available in plant foods, with the exception of vitamin B<sub>12</sub>, which can be obtained only from B<sub>12</sub>-fortified vegan foods or supplements. [[Iodine]] may also require supplementation, such as using iodized salt.<ref name=\"andjrnl.org\">[http://www.andjrnl.org/article/S2212-2672(16)31192-3/abstract#/article/S2212-2672(16)31192-3/fulltext (2016)(Full text) \"Position of the Academy of Nutrition and Dietetics: Vegetarian Diets.], J Acad Nutr Diet. 2016 Dec;116(12):1970-1980.</ref>\n\n== Nutritional deficiencies ==\n\n=== Vitamin B<sub>12</sub> ===\n{{further|Vitamin B12 deficiency}}\n[[File:Vegan food pyramid.svg|alt=|thumb|Vegan food pyramid based on suggestions from the [[American Dietetic Association]]]]\nVitamin B<sub>12</sub> is not made by plants or animals, but by bacteria that grow in soil, feces, dirty water, the intestines of animals or laboratories,<ref name=\"Fang\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Fang H, Kang J, Zhang D | title =Microbial production of vitamin 12: a review and future perspectives | journal = Microbial Cell Factories | volume = 16 | issue = 1 | pages = 15 | date = January 2017 | pmid = 28137297 | pmc = 5282855 | doi = 10.1186/s12934-017-0631-y }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Moore SJ, Warren MJ | title = The anaerobic biosynthesis of vitamin B<sub>12</sub>12 | journal = Biochemical Society Transactions | volume = 40 | issue = 3 | pages = 581\u20136 | date = June 2012 | pmid = 22616870 | doi = 10.1042/BST20120066 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Graham|first1=Ross M.|last2=Deery|first2=Evelyne|last3=Warren|first3=Martin J.|editor1-last=Warren|editor1-first=Martin J.|editor2-last=Smith|editor2-first=Alison G.|editor2-link=Alison Gail Smith | name-list-format = vanc |title=Tetrapyrroles Birth, Life and Death|date=2009|publisher=Springer-Verlag|location=New York, NY|isbn=978-0-387-78518-9|page=286|chapter=18: Vitamin B<sub>12</sub>: Biosynthesis of the Corrin Ring|doi=10.1007/978-0-387-78518-9_18}}</ref><ref name=BPE>{{cite news|last1=Rooke|first1=Jennifer| name-list-format = vanc |title=Do carnivores need Vitamin B<sub>12</sub> supplements?|url=http://baltimorepostexaminer.com/carnivores-need-vitamin-b12-supplements/2013/10/30|work=Baltimore Post Examiner|date=October 30, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Vitamin B<sub>12</sub>|url=http://www.dsm.com/markets/anh/en_US/Compendium/companion_animals/vitamin_B12.html|publisher=DSM|access-date=January 17, 2017}}</ref> so plant foods are not reliable sources of B<sub>12</sub>.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ods.od.nih.gov/factsheets/vitaminb12.asp |title=Dietary Supplement Fact Sheet: Vitamin B<sub>12</sub> |accessdate=2018-02-02 |quote= Strict vegetarians and vegans are at greater risk than lacto-ovo vegetarians and nonvegetarians of developing vitamin B<sub>12</sub> deficiency because natural food sources of vitamin B<sub>12</sub> are limited to animal foods. |publisher=[[National Institutes of Health]]: Office of Dietary Supplements }}</ref> The UK [[Vegan Society]], the Vegetarian Resource Group, and the [[Physicians Committee for Responsible Medicine]], among others, recommend that every vegan consume adequate B<sub>12</sub> either from [[food fortification|fortified foods]] or by taking a supplement.<ref name=\"watanabe20072\">{{cite journal|year=2007|title=Vitamin B<sub>12</sub> sources and bioavailability|url=|journal=Experimental Biology and Medicine |volume=232|issue=10|pages=1266\u20131274|doi=10.3181/0703-MR-67|pmid=17959839|last=Watanabe|first=F.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Vegan Society B<sub>12</sub> factsheet|url=http://www.vegansociety.com/food/nutrition/b12/|last=Walsh|first=Stephen|publisher=Vegan Society|accessdate=January 17, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080526073658/http://www.vegansociety.com/food/nutrition/b12/|archive-date=May 26, 2008|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"vrg.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vrg.org/nutrition/b12.htm |title=Vitamin B<sub>12</sub> in the Vegan Diet |accessdate=January 17, 2008|authorlink=Reed Mangels|last=Mangels|first=Reed|publisher=Vegetarian Resource Group}}</ref><ref name=\"B12PCRM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pcrm.org/health/diets/vegdiets/dont-vegetarians-have-trouble-getting-enough |title=Don't Vegetarians Have Trouble Getting Enough Vitamin B<sub>12</sub>? |accessdate=January 17, 2008 |publisher=[[Physicians Committee for Responsible Medicine]]}}</ref>\n\nVitamin B<sub>12</sub> deficiency is potentially extremely serious, leading to [[megaloblastic anemia]], nerve degeneration and irreversible neurological damage.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=C. |first1=Robert  | last2=Brown |first2=David  |url=http://www.aafp.org/afp/2003/0301/p979.html |title=Vitamin B<sub>12</sub> Deficiency |journal=American Family Physician  |volume=67 |issue=5 |pages=979\u2013986 |date=2003-03-01}}</ref>  Because B<sub>12</sub> is stored in large amounts in the liver, deficiency in adults may begin only years after adoption ofa diet lacking B<sub>12</sub>.  For infants and young children who have not built up these stores, onset of B<sub>12</sub> deficiency can be faster and supplementation for vegan children is thus crucial.\n\nEvidence shows that vegans who are not taking vitamin B<sub>12</sub> supplements do not consume sufficient B<sub>12</sub> and often have abnormally low blood concentrations of vitamin B<sub>12</sub>.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1159/000012827 |title=Homocysteine Levels in Vegetarians versus Omnivores |year=2000 |last1=Kraj\u010dovi\u010dov\u00e1-Kudl\u00e1\u010dkov\u00e1 |first1=M. |last2=Bla\u017e\u00ed\u010dek |first2=P. |last3=Kop\u010dov\u00e1 |first3=J. |last4=B\u00e9derov\u00e1|first4=A. |last5=Babinsk\u00e1 |first5=K. |journal=Annals of Nutrition and Metabolism |volume=44 |issue=3 |pages=135\u20138 |pmid=11053901}}</ref>  This is because, unless fortified, plant foods do not contain reliable amounts of active vitamin B<sub>12</sub>. Vegans are advised to adopt one of the following dietary options:<ref>{{cite web|title = What Every Vegan Should Know About Vitamin B12|url = https://www.vegansociety.com/resources/nutrition-health/vitamins-minerals-and-more/vitamin-b12-your-key-facts/what-every-vegan-should-know-about-vitamin-b12|accessdate = 2015-08-05}}</ref> \n* Consume fortified foods 2-3 times per day to get at least 3 micrograms of vitamin B<sub>12</sub>,\n* or take 10 micrograms of B<sub>12</sub> as a supplement once per day\n* or take 2000 micrograms of B<sub>12</sub> as a supplement once per week\n\nB<sub>12</sub> is more efficiently absorbed in small regular doses, which explains why the quantity required rises so quickly as frequency goes down.\n\nThe US National Institutes of Health recommends B<sub>12</sub> intake in a range from 0.4 micrograms a day for infants, to 2.4 micrograms for adults, and up to 2.8 micrograms for nursing mothers.\n<ref>[https://ods.od.nih.gov/factsheets/VitaminB12-Consumer/#h2 \"Vitamin B<sub>12</sub>: Fact Sheet for Consumers\"] National Institutes of Health Office of Dietary Supplements (retrieved Dec 9, 2016)</ref>\nThe European Food Safety Authority set the Adequate Intake at 1.5 micrograms for infants, 4 micrograms for children and adults, and 4.5 and 5 micrograms during pregnancy and nursing.<ref>[http://www.efsa.europa.eu/en/efsajournal/pub/4150 \"Scientific Opinion on Dietary Reference Values for cobalamin (vitamin B<sub>12</sub>)\"] European Food Safety Authority Panel on Dietetic Products, Nutrition and Allergies. EFSA Journal 2015;13(7):4150 [64 pp.].</ref> These amounts can be obtained by eating B<sub>12</sub> fortified foods, which include some common breakfast cereals, soy milks, and meat analogues, as well as from common [[multivitamin]]s such as [[One-A-Day]]. Some of the fortified foods require only a single serving to provide the recommended B<sub>12</sub> amounts.\n<ref>[http://www.pcrm.org/health/diets/vegdiets/dont-vegetarians-have-trouble-getting-enough \"Don't Vegetarians Have Trouble Getting Enough Vitamin B<sub>12</sub>?\"] Physicians Committee for Responsible Medicine (retrieved Dec 9, 2016)</ref>\n\nOther B<sub>12</sub> fortified foods may include some almond milks, coconut milks, other plant milks, nutritional yeast, vegan mayonnaise, tofu, and various types and brands of vegan deli slices, burgers, and other veggie meats.\n\n=== Protein ===\n\n{{See also|Protein deficiency|Protein quality}}\n\nUpon digestion, all protein foods supply [[amino acid]]s. Varied intake of plant foods can meet human health needs for protein and amino acids.<ref name=melina/><ref name=\"andjrnl.org\"/> Foods high in protein in a vegan diet include [[legume]]s (such as beans and [[lentil]]s), nuts, seeds, and grains (such as oats, wheat, and [[quinoa]]).<ref name=melina/><ref name=\"healthscopemag\">{{cite web|url=https://www.healthscopemag.com/health-scope/plating-more-plant-based-protein/ |title=Plating More Plant-Based Protein |publisher=Healthscope Magazine |url-status=live |accessdate = 2015-08-15}}</ref>\n\n=== Omega-3 fatty acids ===\n[[File:Flax seeds.jpg|thumb|[[Flaxseed]]s are a rich source of ALA, the precursor to DHA and EPA, the [[omega-3 fatty acids]]]] \n[[File:English Walnuts.jpg|thumb|[[Walnuts]] are another rich source of ALA, the precursor to DHA and EPA, the [[omega-3 fatty acid|omega-3 oil]]s]]\n\nMajor vegan sources of the essential [[omega-3 fatty acid]] ALA include [[walnut]]s, [[flax|flaxseeds and flaxseed oil]], [[canola]] ([[rapeseed]]) oil, [[algae]] oil, [[hemp|hempseeds and hempseed oil]], [[olive oil]], and [[avocado]].<ref name=\"andjrnl.org\"/>\n\nDiets without seafood are lower in non-essential long-chain [[omega-3 fatty acid]]s like DHA and EPA. Short-term supplemental ALA has been shown to increase EPA levels, but not DHA levels, suggesting limited conversion of the intermediary EPA to DHA.<ref name=\"dha\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.plefa.2009.05.013 |title=DHA status of vegetarians |year=2009 |last1=Sanders |first1=Thomas A.B. |journal=Prostaglandins, Leukotrienes and Essential Fatty Acids |volume=81 |issue=2\u20133 |pmid=19500961 |pages=137\u201341}}</ref> DHA supplements derived from DHA-rich [[alga|microalgae]] are available, and the human body can also convert DHA to EPA.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Colette |last1=Bouchez |title=Good Fat, Bad Fat: The Facts About Omega-3 |url=http://women.webmd.com/features/omega-3-fatty-acids |website=[[WebMD]]}}</ref> Although omega-3 has previously been thought useful for helping alleviate [[dementia]], {{asof|2016|lc=yes}}, there is no good evidence of effectiveness.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Burckhardt M, Herke M, Wustmann T, Watzke S, Langer G, Fink A |title=Omega-3 fatty acids for the treatment of dementia |journal=Cochrane Database Syst Rev |volume=4 |issue= |pages=CD009002 |year=2016 |pmid=27063583 |doi=10.1002/14651858.CD009002.pub3 |type=Systematic review|pmc=7117565 }}</ref>\n\nWhile there is little evidence of adverse health or cognitive effects due to DHA deficiency in adult vegetarians or vegans, fetal and breast milk levels remain a concern.<ref name=\"dha\" /> EPA and DHA supplementation has been shown to reduce platelet aggregation in vegetarians, but a direct link to cardiovascular morbidity and mortality, which is already lower for vegetarians, has yet to be determined.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/S0049-3848(00)00313-3 |title=Cardiovascular Risk Factors in Vegetarians: Normalization of Hyperhomocysteinemia with Vitamin B<sub>12</sub> and Reduction of Platelet Aggregation with n-3 Fatty Acids |year=2000 |last1=Mezzano |first1=Diego |last2=Kosiel |first2=Karin |last3=Mart\u00ednez |first3=Carlos |last4=Cuevas |first4=Ada |last5=Panes |first5=Olga |last6=Aranda |first6=Eduardo |last7=Strobel |first7=Pablo |last8=P\u00e9rez |first8=Druso D |last9=Pereira |first9=Jaime |last10=Rozowski |first10=Jaime |last11=Leighton |first11=Federico |journal=[[Thrombosis Research]] |volume=100 |issue=3 |pages=153\u201360 |pmid=11108902|display-authors=9 }}</ref>\n\n=== Calcium ===\nIt is recommended that vegans eat three servings per day of a high-[[calcium]] food, such as [[Food fortification|fortified]] [[plant milk]]s, green leafy vegetables, seeds, [[tofu]], or other calcium-rich foods, and take a calcium supplement as necessary.<ref name=melina/><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Craig|first=Winston J|date=2009-03-11|title=Health effects of vegan diets|journal=The American Journal of Clinical Nutrition|language=en|volume=89|issue=5|pages=1627S\u20131633S|doi=10.3945/ajcn.2009.26736N|pmid=19279075|issn=0002-9165|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nMany studies have examined possible correlation between veganism, calcium intake, and bone health. The [[European Prospective Investigation into Cancer and Nutrition|EPIC-Oxford]] study suggested that vegans who consumed 525&nbsp;mg or less of calcium per day have an increased risk of bone fractures over meat eaters and vegetarians, but that vegans consuming more than 525&nbsp;mg/day had a risk of fractures similar to other groups. Overall, the entire group of vegans had a higher risk of fractures.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1038/sj.ejcn.1602659 |title=Comparative fracture risk in vegetarians and nonvegetarians in EPIC-Oxford |year=2007 |last1=Appleby |first1=P |last2=Roddam |first2=A |last3=Allen |first3=N |last4=Key |first4=T |journal=European Journal of Clinical Nutrition |volume=61 |issue=12 |pages=1400\u20136 |pmid=17299475|doi-access=free }}</ref> A 2009 study of bone density found the bone density of vegans was 94 percent that of omnivores, but deemed the difference clinically insignificant.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.3945/ajcn.2009.27521 |title=Effect of vegetarian diets on bone mineral density: A Bayesian meta-analysis |year=2009 |last1=Ho-Pham |first1=L. T |last2=Nguyen |first2=N. D |last3=Nguyen |first3=T. V |journal=American Journal of Clinical Nutrition |volume=90 |issue=4 |pages=943\u201350 |pmid=19571226|doi-access=free }}</ref> Another study in 2009 by the same researchers examined over 100 vegan post-menopausal women, and found that their diet had no adverse effect on bone mineral density (BMD) and no alteration in body composition.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1007/s00198-009-0916-z |title=Veganism, bone mineral density, and body composition: A study in Buddhist nuns |year=2009 |last1=Ho-Pham |first1=L. T. |last2=Nguyen |first2=P. L. T. |last3=Le |first3=T. T. T. |last4=Doan |first4=T. A. T. |last5=Tran |first5=N. T. |last6=Le |first6=T. A. |last7=Nguyen |first7=T. V. |journal=Osteoporosis International |volume=20 |issue=12 |pages=2087\u201393 |pmid=19350341}}</ref> Biochemist [[T. Colin Campbell]] suggested in ''[[The China Study]]'' (2005) that [[osteoporosis]] is linked to the consumption of animal protein because, unlike plant protein, animal protein increases the acidity of blood and tissues, which he believed was neutralized by calcium pulled from the bones resulting in [[hypercalciuria]]. Campbell wrote that his [[China-Oxford-Cornell Study on Dietary, Lifestyle and Disease Mortality Characteristics in 65 Rural Chinese Counties|China-Oxford-Cornell study]] of nutrition in the 1970s and 1980s found that, in rural China, \"where the animal to plant ratio [for protein] was about 10 percent, the fracture rate is only one-fifth that of the U.S.\"<ref>Campbell, T. Colin. [https://books.google.com/books?id=KgRR12F0RPAC&pg=PA205 ''The China Study'']. Benbella Books, 2006, pp. 205\u2013208.</ref>\n\nCalcium is one component of the most common type of human kidney stones, [[calcium oxalate]]. Some studies suggest that people who take [[dietary supplement|supplemental calcium]] have a higher risk of developing kidney stones, and these findings have been used as the basis for setting the [[Reference Daily Intake|recommended daily intake]] (RDI) for calcium in adults.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Brody |first1=Jane E. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/05/08/science/huge-study-of-diet-indicts-fat-and-meat.html |title=Huge Study Of Diet Indicts Fat And Meat |work=The New York Times |date=May 8, 1990}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Junshi |editor1-first=Chen |editor2-last=Campbell |editor2-first=T. Colin |editor3-last=Li |editor4-last=Peto |editor4-first=R. | displayeditors = 3|title=Diet, lifestyle, and mortality in China: a study of the characteristics of 65 Chinese counties |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=1990 |isbn=978-0-19-261843-6}}{{page needed|date=June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Byers |first1=Tim |url=http://aje.oxfordjournals.org/content/135/10/1180.extract |title=Book Reviews: Diet, lifestyle, and mortality in China: a study of the characteristics of 65 Chinese counties |journal=American Journal of Epidemiology |volume=135 |issue=10 |pages=1180\u20131 |date=1992-05-15|doi=10.1093/oxfordjournals.aje.a116219 }}</ref>\n\n=== Iodine ===\n\nOne study reported a \"potential danger of [[iodine]] deficiency disorders due to strict forms of vegetarian nutrition, especially when fruits and vegetables grown in soils with low [iodine] levels are ingested.\"<ref>{{cite journal |first1=Thomas |last1=Remer |first2=Annette |last2=Neubert |first3=Friedrich |last3=Manz |title=Increased risk of iodine deficiency with vegetarian nutrition |journal=British Journal of Nutrition |pmid=10341675 |year=1999 |volume=81 |issue=1 |pages=45\u20139 |doi=10.1017/s0007114599000136|doi-access=free }}</ref> Vegan diets typically require special attention for iodine, for which the only substantial and reliable vegan sources are sea vegetables, iodized salt and supplements. The iodine content of sea vegetables varies widely and may provide more than the recommended upper limit of iodine intake.<ref name=\"andjrnl.org\"/>\n\n=== Iron ===\nIt is recommended for vegans to eat iron-rich foods and vitamin C daily.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/bhcv2/bhcarticles.nsf/pages/iron_deficiency_adults?open|title=Iron deficiency\u2014adults|quote=High-risk groups such as vegetarians, adolescent girls and women athletes need to eat iron-rich foods each day (combined with foods that are high in vitamin C). ... Vegetarians who exclude all animal products from their diet may need almost twice as much dietary iron each day as non-vegetarians. Sources include dark green leafy vegetables\u2014such as spinach\u2014and raisins, nuts, seeds, beans, peas, and iron-fortified cereals, breads and pastas}}</ref> In several studies, vegans were not found to suffer from [[iron]]-deficiency any more than non-vegans.<ref>{{cite journal |pmid=12081822 |year=2002 |last1=Larsson |first1=CL |last2=Johansson |first2=GK |title=Dietary intake and nutritional status of young vegans and omnivores in Sweden |volume=76 |issue=1 |pages=100\u20136 |journal=The American Journal of Clinical Nutrition|doi=10.1093/ajcn/76.1.100 |doi-access=free }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Messina |first1=MJ |last2=Messina |first2=VL |title=The Dietitian's Guide to Vegetarian Diets: Issues and Applications |location=Gaithersburg, MD |publisher=Aspen Publishers |year=1996}}{{page needed|date=June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |pmid=8172127 |year=1994 |last1=Craig |first1=WJ |title=Iron status of vegetarians |volume=59 |issue=5 Suppl |pages=1233S\u20131237S |journal=The American Journal of Clinical Nutrition|doi=10.1093/ajcn/59.5.1233S }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |pmid=10479197 |year=1999 |last1=Ball |first1=MJ |last2=Bartlett |first2=MA |title=Dietary intake and iron status of Australian vegetarian women |volume=70 |issue=3 |pages=353\u20138 |journal=The American Journal of Clinical Nutrition|doi=10.1093/ajcn/70.3.353 |doi-access=free }}</ref> However, due to the low absorption rate on non-heme iron it is recommended to eat dark leafy greens (and other sources of iron) together with sources of Vitamin C.<ref>{{Cite journal|quote=The key role of ascorbic acid for the absorption of dietary nonheme iron is generally accepted. The reasons for its action are twofold: (1) the prevention of the formation of insoluble and unabsorbable iron compounds and (2) the reduction of ferric to ferrous iron, which seems to be a requirement for the uptake of iron into the mucosal cells.|title=The role of vitamin C in iron absorption|journal=International Journal for Vitamin and Nutrition Research. Supplement|volume=30|pages=103\u20138|pmid=2507689|year=1989|last1=Hallberg|first1=L|last2=Brune|first2=M|last3=Rossander|first3=L}}</ref> Iron supplementation should be taken at different times to other supplements with a 2+ [[valence (chemistry)]] such as calcium or magnesium, as they inhibit the absorption of iron.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=L\u00f6nnerdal |first1=B |title=Calcium and iron absorption--mechanisms and public health relevance. |journal=Int J Vitam Nutr Res |date=October 2010 |volume=90 |issue=4\u20135 |pages=293\u20139 |doi=10.1024/0300-9831/a000036 |pmid=21462112 }}</ref>\n\n=== Choline ===\n{{Importance section|date=January 2019}}\nDue to lack of evidence, no country has published a recommended daily intake for [[choline]], which is a vitamin-like essential nutrient.  The Australian, New Zealand, and European Union national nutrition bodies note there have been no reports of choline deficiency in the general population.<ref>{{citation|title=Nutrient Reference Values for Australia and New Zealand|url=https://www.nrv.gov.au/nutrients/choline|quote=Although choline is essential, there appear to have been no reports of deficiency in the general population. Deficiencies have been seen in experimental situations and also in total parenteral nutrition (Buchman et al. 1992, 1993, 1995, Chalwa et al. 1989, Shapira et al. 1986, Sheard et al. 1986).}}</ref> There are, however, Adequate Intakes such as the European Union's number of 400&nbsp;mg/day for adults, and the US's number of 425&nbsp;mg/day for adult non-pregnant women and 550&nbsp;mg/day for adult men.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ods.od.nih.gov/factsheets/Choline-HealthProfessional/|title=Choline|publisher=Office of Dietary Supplements, US National Institutes of Health|date=26 September 2018|accessdate=26 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nCholine deficiency, as created in lab conditions, can lead to health problems such as liver damage, a result of liver cells initiating programmed cell death (apoptosis), as well as an increase in neural tube defects in pregnant women.<ref name=\"Higdon\">{{cite web |last=Higdon |first=Jane |title=Choline |publisher=Linus Pauling Institute at Oregon State University |date=Nov 2003 |url=http://lpi.oregonstate.edu/infocenter/othernuts/choline/ |accessdate=3 March 2014}}</ref> In a study, 77% of men, 44% of premenopausal women, and 80% of postmenopausal women developed fatty liver or muscle damage due to choline deficiency, showing that subject characteristics regulate the dietary requirement.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Fischer |first=Leslie M. |last2=DaCosta |first2=Kerry A. |last3=Kwock |first3=Lester |last4=Stewart |first4=Paul W. |last5=Lu |first5=Tsui-Shan |last6=Stabler |first6=Sally P. |last7=Allen |first7=Robert H. |last8=Zeisel |first8=Steven H. |title=Sex and Menopausal Status Influence Human Dietary Requirements for the Nutrient Choline |journal=The American Journal of Clinical Nutrition |volume=85 |issue=5 |pages=1275\u20131285 |date=May 2007 |doi=10.1093/ajcn/85.5.1275 |pmid=17490963 |pmc=2435503 }}</ref>  There is also some evidence that choline is an anti-inflammatory as well, but further studies are needed to confirm/refute findings.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Paraskevi |first=Detopoulou |last2=Panagiotakos |first2=Demosthenes B. |last3=Antonopoulou |first3=Smaragdi |last4=Pitsavos |first4=Christos |last5=Stefanadis |first5=Christodoulos |title=Dietary Choline and Betaine Intakes in Relation to Concentrations of Inflammatory Markers in Healthy Adults: The ATTICA Study |journal=The American Journal of Clinical Nutrition |volume=87 |issue=2 |pages=424\u2013430 |date=5 Sep 2007 |doi=10.1093/ajcn/87.2.424 |pmid=18258634 |doi-access=free }}</ref> It is worth noting that many multivitamins do not contain the Adequate Intake of choline.<ref>{{cite journal |last=McCord |first=BreAnn |title=Multivitamins Lack Choline |place=Beloit College }}</ref>\n\nAlthough many animal products, like liver and egg, contain high amounts of choline (355&nbsp;mg/3 oz and 126&nbsp;mg/large egg, respectively), wheat germ (172&nbsp;mg/cup), brussel sprouts (63&nbsp;mg/cup), and broccoli (62&nbsp;mg/cup) are also good sources of choline.<ref name=\"Higdon\"/>  Other sources include soy lecithin, cauliflower, spinach, wheat germ, firm tofu, kidney beans, quinoa and amaranth.\n\n=== Vitamin D ===\nThe main function of vitamin D in the body is increased absorption of calcium, therefore it is good for the bones. It also connects with receptors in the prostate, the heart, blood vessels, muscles, [[endocrine gland]]s and others.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.health.harvard.edu/staying-healthy/vitamin-d-and-your-health-breaking-old-rules-raising-new-hopes |author=Harvard Men's Health Watch |title=Vitamin D and your health: Breaking old rules, raising new hopes |publisher=Harvard MEdical School |date=February 2007 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSunlight, fortified foods, and supplements, are the main sources of vitamin D for vegans. Humans produce [[vitamin D]] naturally in response to [[Ultraviolet|ultraviolet light]] (UV). Complete cloud cover reduces UV penetration by up to 50%, and outdoor shade reduces UV penetration by 60%. UV light penetrates the skin at wavelengths between 290 and 320 nanometers, where it is then converted into vitamin D3.<ref name=\"healthpro\">{{cite web|url=https://ods.od.nih.gov/factsheets/VitaminD-HealthProfessional/ |author=US National Institute of Health |title=Vitamin D Fact Sheet for Health Professionals |publisher=US National Institute of Health |url-status=live}}</ref> Vitamin D2 can be obtained from [[fungus|fungi]], such as [[mushroom]]s exposed to sun or industrial [[ultraviolet light]], offering a vegan choice for dietary or supplemental vitamin D.<ref name=usda-mush-light>{{cite web|author=Haytowitz DB|title=Vitamin D in mushrooms|url=https://www.ars.usda.gov/ARSUserFiles/80400525/Articles/AICR09_Mushroom_VitD.pdf|publisher=Nutrient Data Laboratory, US Department of Agriculture|accessdate=16 April 2018|date=2009}}</ref><ref name=\"keegan\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Keegan RJ, Lu Z, Bogusz JM, Williams JE, Holick MF | title = Photobiology of vitamin D in mushrooms and its bioavailability in humans | journal = Dermato-Endocrinology | volume = 5 | issue = 1 | pages = 165\u201376 | date = January 2013 | pmid = 24494050 | pmc = 3897585 | doi = 10.4161/derm.23321 }}</ref>\n\nAlthough vitamin D3 is produced in small amounts by [[lichen]]s or [[algae]] exposed to sunlight,<ref name=\"bjorn\">{{cite journal | last=Bj\u00f6rn | first=LO | last2=Wang | first2=T | title=Vitamin D in an ecological context. | journal=International Journal of Circumpolar Health | volume=59 | issue=1 | year=2000 | issn=1239-9736 | pmid=10850004 | pages=26\u201332}}</ref><ref name=\"japelt\">{{cite journal | last=J\u00e4pelt | first=Rie B. | last2=Jakobsen | first2=Jette | title=Vitamin D in plants: a review of occurrence, analysis, and biosynthesis | journal=Frontiers in Plant Science| volume=4 | pages=136 | year=2013 | issn=1664-462X | doi=10.3389/fpls.2013.00136 | pmid=23717318|pmc=3651966}}</ref> industrial production in commercial quantities is limited, and there are few supplement products as of 2019.<ref name=\"nutra\">{{cite web |author=Adi Menayang| title=AIDP: \"There is a significant market potential for vegan D3\" | publisher=NutraIngredients-USA, William Reed, Inc | date=29 April 2019 | url=https://www.nutraingredients-usa.com/Article/2019/04/29/AIDP-There-is-a-significant-market-potential-for-vegan-D3 | access-date=10 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe recommended daily allowance in vitamin D for adults under the age of 70 years old is between 600 and 4,000 [[international unit|IU]], and for adults over 70 years old, 800 to 4,000 IU.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dietitians.ca/getattachment/464f3006-0bb2-4f1a-a338-0b21d148bacb/FACTSHEET-Food-Sources-of-Vitamin-D.pdf.aspx |author=Detitians of Canada |title=Food Sources of Vitamin D |publisher=Dietitians of Canada |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nReports on exactly how much vitamin D is produced by exposure to sunlight are wild and varied, across the board.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Vegetarian nutrition]]\n* [[Nutrition]]\n* [[Raw veganism]]\n* [[Orthomolecular medicine|Nutritional medicine]]\n* ''[[The China Study]]'' from 2005\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Vegetarianism}}\n\n[[Category:Veganism]]\n", "name_user": "Mx. Granger", "label": "safe", "comment": "copyediting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vegan_nutrition"}
